{Hello, my name is Dalton Perrine, and along with Grandmaster Sam Shankland, who is presenting the videos, we welcome you to this Chessable course! I'm a FIDE Master with 10 years of coaching experience, having taught hundreds of students in both 1-on-1 and group settings. Over the course of my coaching career, I’ve found that students tend to struggle most with evaluating positions, recognizing what constitutes an ‘advantage’, gaining advantages in the first place, and ultimately figuring out how to convert advantages in the middlegame into a win. If you've ever played a game, had a significant advantage at some point, but squandered it and failed to win, then this course is for you! In this course, you will be learning a variety of advantages that you can have during a chess game, how to gain these advantages in your own games, and how to convert these advantages into wins as efficiently as possible. In addition to learning about advantages, I'll also be explaining many different kinds of tools that you can use to convert these advantages, as well as giving you a variety of blueprints to follow based on what kind of advantage you may have in a position.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction − Static vs. Dynamic Advantage"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654359812086"]

{Generally speaking, in chess there are two categories of advantages that you can have at any point during a game: 1. Static advantages 2. Dynamic advantages To begin with, static advantages are more of a long-term variety. These types of advantages are ones that will generally not disappear as the game continues its normal progression unless one side makes a concerted effort to change things. Examples of static advantages include: 1. King Safety 2. Material 3. Bishop Pair 4. Space 5. Pawn Weakness If one side possesses any of these advantages during the game, then it is usually something they can work with for a longer stretch of moves. This is different from dynamic advantages which we'll discuss next. For example: If you are ahead a pawn, then you will continue to be ahead a pawn unless you sacrifice it on purpose or blunder it by accident. Also, if your opponent has a weak isolated pawn, then it will continue to stay on the board and be weak unless your opponent makes a concerted effort to try to trade it off in some way. These advantages don't just disappear 'overnight' without considerable effort from one of the two players. On the other hand, dynamic advantages are the types of advantages that are more short-term in nature. These types of advantages are ones that will usually disappear as the game continues its normal progression, especially if they are not used and taken advantage of quickly. Examples of dynamic advantages include: 1. Lead in Development 2. Uncastled King 3. Piece Activity 4. Initiative/Time If one side possesses any of these advantages during the game, then it is usually something that doesn't last for a long stretch of moves. For example: If you have a lead in development, then this advantage is temporary since the opponent will be able to catch up in development as the game continues. Also, if your opponent has the initiative and is creating a series of threats that you're reacting to, this situation will usually not last forever; there will come a time when they will stop creating threats, and their initiative may very well lose momentum or die down. Compared to static advantages, dynamic advantages do disappear 'overnight' if they are not used quickly. In this course, we will be focusing on how to utilize static (long-term) advantages.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
