{White just played 19.Nb3. What is their idea and how should Black play in response?} 19... Bf8 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf8c5,Gb3c5] It's a good idea for Black to discourage White's potential knight jump to the strong [c5]-square. If this knight could move there without being challenged, then it would be an annoying piece for us to deal with on our half of the board. Black has a spatial advantage on the queenside; we should aim to prevent White from easily improving their position.} (19... Ng4 $4 {This is a perfect example of a move we want to play, but we fail to first consider what our opponent wants to do!} 20. Nc5 {+- , if White gets the chance to hop over to the [c5]-square, then Black could face some annoying pressure on both the [a6]-bishop and the [e6]-pawn, and we would actually lose material here due to this fork tactic. We should prevent this from happening!}) 20. Nc5 {If White tries jumping here anyways, we will quickly eliminate this piece.} Bxc5 21. dxc5 d4 {Pushing the bishop back and making it difficult for White to defend their [c5]-pawn.} 22. Bf2 (22. Bxd4 $4 {Capturing the pawn opens too many lines for our pieces.} Nxd4 23. Qxd4 Rd8 $1 {Attacking the queen with the goal of pushing it away from defending [c5].} 24. Qe3 Ng4 {-+ , we continue kicking White's queen and now it has to move away from defending the [c5]-pawn. We'll capture on [c5] next, with a very dangerous position for White.}) 22... Rd8 $19 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gh6g4] The [c5]-pawn will most likely drop within a few moves. Playing ...[Ng4] is also possible to trade off White's dark-squared bishop.} *

