{Black is very tied up here with most of their pieces stuck defending something else. What move would they like to play to have a bit less pressure on their position? Can we prevent that move?} 1. b6 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rc5,Rf6] This strong move prevents Black from stabilizing their pawn structure on the queenside. The [c5]-pawn cannot be defended by the b-pawn and the b-pawn is stuck on [b7], which means the rook is stuck on [b8]. Black's queen cannot take the pawn because it needs to defend [f6]. All of Black's pieces are frozen and White will capture [f6] followed by [b7] with a winning advantage.} (1. Nxc5 $2 {Capturing the pawn doesn't work for White.} Qb6 2. Qd4 {and it might seem like White has everything under control since ...[Qxa7] runs into [Nxe6]+ winning the queen. However, Black has a cold-blooded idea of their own:} Bxc4 {. Black eliminates the [c4]-pawn and will capture [b5] next. The position is very drawish now.}) (1. Kf2 $2 {A move like this doesn't prevent Black's idea. After} b6 {⩲ , White is still better, but Black has been able to relieve some pressure on the [b7] and [c5]-pawns. Next, they will play ...[Qd4] to trade queens.}) (1. Nxf6 $2 {Trading on [f6] too quickly allows Black to hold the position.} Qxf6 2. Qxf6+ Kxf6 3. Rxb7 Rxb7 4. Bxb7 Bxc4 5. b6 Ke7 {⩲ and Black's king is just close enough to deal with the b-pawn pushing. White is one tempo behind compared to the main line where they played [b6] on the first move.}) 1... Qd4+ {This gets the queens off the board but costs Black their b-pawn.} 2. Qxd4 cxd4 3. Nxf6 Kxf6 4. Rxb7 {[%csl Gb6] White has a winning advantage due to their passed b-pawn.} Rxb7 5. Bxb7 Bxc4 {Black has equalized material, but the b-pawn will win us the game.} 6. Bc8 Bd5 7. b7 Bxb7 8. Bxb7 $18 {White wins the endgame easily with the extra piece.} *

