{How can we heavily restrict one of Black's pieces?} 17. b3 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gb3c4,Gb3a4] Now the knight on [b6] has no good squares to move forward to.} (17. Rh1 $6 {If we focus on our own plans and ignore the opponent's ideas, then this could hurt us. Following} Nc4 18. Bc1 Qb6 {∞ , Black has been able to activate their pieces and put more pressure on our [b2] and [d4]-pawns. We shouldn't allow this to happen.}) 17... Rc8 {Black develops their rook. Is there anything we need to be careful about here?} (17... Bxh4 $2 {We don't need to be troubled by Black capturing our [h4]-pawn.} 18. g5 {+- , the bishop is trapped, and Black can only save it by sacrificing material.}) 18. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gc8c3] Black was threatening to make a discovered attack towards our undefended knight on [c3]. We can simply move the knight away and avoid any trouble. Black will soon run out of counterplay and continue to have a bad position in the long term.} (18. Rh1 $2 {Ignoring our opponent's moves and ideas would be painful here.} Nxe5 $1 19. Nxe5 Rxc3 {∞ and Black has won a pawn. There's no need to allow this.}) (18. Rc1 $4 {defends the knight but allows Black to win material:} Ba3 $1 19. Rc2 Nb4 {-+ . One of the two pieces on the c-file is now doomed to fall. If the rook moves, we'll lose the knight. Otherwise, we'll be down an exchange.}) *

