{White has a pawn on [c2] that needs to be protected by their queen. How can Black play against this?} 13... Qf8 $1 {Offering an exchange of queens, which would result in White losing their defense of the [c2]-pawn. White's queen is the glue to their position and getting rid of it causes them a lot of trouble.} 14. Qxf8+ {White could not avoid the queen exchange.} (14. Qd2 $4 {Avoiding the queen trade would backfire horribly.} Nb3 $1 {Black clears the [d4]-square for their bishop, while also forking White's queen and rook.} 15. Bxb3 Bd4+ {+ -+ , White has to block with the queen on [e3] and lose material. Moving the king to [h1] would allow [Qf1]#.}) 14... Bxf8 {Here, Black's bishop does an important job of protecting the [c5]-pawn. White's having difficulty defending their [c2]-pawn.} (14... Kxf8 $6 15. Be3 $1 {White is able to save the pawn tactically since the knight is now pinned to the undefended [c5]-pawn.}) 15. Bb3 {Retreating the bishop was the only way to save the pawn, but now there is an option to play ...[Nxb3] at any moment, which would weaken White's pawn structure and give Black the bishop pair.} b6 16. Be3 Bg7 $17 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gd4b3] Black is in no rush to capture on [b3] since the bishop is tied down to protecting the vulnerable [c2]-pawn. If White tries [Ba4], then we can play ...[a6] and ...[b5] to kick it back to [b3]. Black's position is very pleasant, with the more active pieces and the weakness on [c2].} *

