{Black has a weak square on [d5]. If given the time, Black would like to secure the [e5]-pawn and play ...[d5] themselves to eliminate this weakness. Instead of allowing this, White can gain a good piece vs. bad piece imbalance in their favor.} 1. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg5f6] Pinning the knight, which is helping to fight for control of the [d5]-square. We would like to capture on [f6] and weaken Black's kingside pawn structure as well.} (1. c4 {∞ gains more control over the weak [d5]-square but also weakens our own [d4]-square in the meantime.}) (1. Ne3 {⩲ , leading with the knight is not as good as playing [Bg5] first. We need to eliminate the [f6]-knight, which is controlling the [d5]-square, before we can jump in.}) 1... Qe6 {Defending the knight and avoiding pawn structure problems.} 2. Ne3 {Maneuvering towards controlling the weak [d5]-square.} h6 3. Bxf6 {This trade may seem counterintuitive. Why would we trade a bishop for a knight?! Our goal here is to dominate the weak [d5]-square and leave Black with bad pieces.} Qxf6 4. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Rb6] We have a very strong knight on the [d5]-outpost, with no intention of trading it off anytime soon, unless we get a bigger advantage in return. Even if Black plays ...[Nc6]-[e7] later, we can trade knights and reoccupy the [d5]-square with our remaining knight. In an ideal situation, we will have a strong knight on [d5] against our opponent's very bad dark-squared bishop. Black faces a daunting task in this position, hindered by their poorly coordinated and weak pieces.} *

