{Black has a variety of weaknesses in their position including the backward [e6]-pawn and weak [e5]-square. How can White work towards taking advantage of these things?} 16. Bxc6 $1 {First, Kramnik begins by trading off the [c6]-knight, which was attacking our [d4]-pawn and defending the [e5]-square.} Qxc6 17. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rg7][%cal Ge2g3,Gg3h5,Ge2f4,Gf4d3] Planning to maneuver towards the kingside or [d3]-[e5] squares.} (17. Ne5 {was played in the game and it still led to an advantage for White:} Bxe5 18. Rxe5 Rxe5 19. dxe5 Kg7 20. Ne2 {+- . White has a good knight vs. a bad bishop, and Black's king is very weak. White won the game later with no trouble.}) 17... Be8 {Covering the [h5]-square so that [Ng3]-[h5] isn't possible.} (17... Raf8 {stops [Nf4], but White can also maneuver in a different way. After} 18. Ng3 R5f7 19. Nh5 {+- , White can trade on [g7] next and then put a knight on [e5] later. Black's bishop cannot retreat to [h8] without dropping the [h6]-pawn.}) 18. Nf4 {Heading towards the [d3]-square instead.} Bf7 19. Nd3 $18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd3e5,Gf3e5] White will put a knight on [e5] next, with a great position. The knight on [e5] will be significantly better than Black's bad light-squared bishop.} *

