{A king safety advantage is one where your king is safer than your opponent's king. What kind of things can make this difference? One way this can occur is if your opponent is missing a pawn that would normally be shielding their king; this weakening of the pawn shield makes their king slightly more vulnerable to potential attacks. In this position, we can see that White's king is castled kingside while Black's king is uncastled. However, we also see that White's king's pawn shield is a bit compromised. Usually, the pawns would be on [h2], [g3], and [f2] with the fianchettoed bishop on [g2]. Here though, the h- and g-pawns have advanced forward, which means that there is a bit of open space and less pawn coverage around the king. We can see that Black's [d6]-bishop and [b8]-queen are lined up in that direction looking to possibly exploit this weakness. You can see how the game continued by clicking here.} 1... Z0 *

