[GameId "2133654360377365"]

{Jobava has the option of playing Bxf6 here, which would force Black to recapture with the g-pawn and open up the king. However, instead of rushing to do this immediately, he decides to put more pressure on Black's soft spots first.} 19. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rf6][%cal Gg2b7,Gf3f6,Gg5f6] Not only hitting the [f6]-knight once again but also attacking the [b7]-pawn.} (19. Bxf6 $5 {Trading on [f6] right away is also good for White, but there was no rush to do it immediately.} gxf6 20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Qh4 {± , White continues to have a strong position and good attacking chances towards Black's unsafe king.}) 19... e5 $2 {Black makes a mistake under pressure. The downside of this move is that it weakens the light squares in Black's position, specifically the [d5] and [f5]-squares. We will see how these weaknesses are exploited in a few moves.} (19... Be7 {, sacrificing a pawn on the queenside would have been the lesser of two evils. After} 20. Qxb7 Qxb7 21. Bxb7 Rab8 22. Bxa6 Rxb2 23. a4 {± , White has very good chances to win the endgame with the passed pawns on the queenside.}) 20. Bxf6 {Capturing the knight also attacks the rook on [d8], so Black's reply is forced.} gxf6 {Now Black's king protection is compromised. The next step for White is to maneuver the pieces towards the exposed king and launch an attack.} 21. Nf5 $18 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf3g4] The knight is able to plant iself on the newly weakened [f5]-square. This knight creates deadly threats on the kingside, specifically [Qg4]-[g7] with checkmate, which is a huge problem.} *

