[GameId "2133654360397846"]

{Jobava has weakened his opponent's kingside heavily now that the g-pawn was pulled to the [f6]-square. How can White continue to attack?} 22. Qg4+ Kh8 23. Qh4 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gh4f6] White attacks the [f6]-pawn, which is difficult for Black to defend well.} Qb6 $2 {This defends the pawn but runs into a nice tactical shot.} ({After} 23... Bxf5 {, White doesn't mind if the knight is captured since they will win the piece back quickly.} 24. Qxf6+ Bg7 25. Qxf5 {+- and White continues to have a king safety advantage while also winning a pawn. Next, White will play [Be4] and attack the [h7]-pawn.}) (23... Bg7 {is probably Black's best defense, but White will continue to attack the exposed king anyway. Following} 24. Qg4 Rg8 25. Qh5 Be6 26. Be4 Bf8 27. Ne3 {+- , White is able to continue putting a lot of pressure on Black's kingside.}) 24. Rd6 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Rf6][%cal Gd6b6,Gh4f6] White interferes with Black's horizontal defense and is willing to sacrifice the rook to accomplish this!} Qxb2 ({Capturing the rook walks into a mating attack:} 24... Bxd6 25. Qxf6+ Kg8 26. Qg7# {.}) 25. Qxf6+ Kg8 26. Qg5+ Kh8 27. Rad1 $18 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gd1d8] Black resigned here since they were going to lose material soon due to the pin along the d-file. White did a great job of first opening up Black's king protection and then maneuvering to attack the weaknesses. This was aided by some tactics along the way too.} 1-0

