{Black has the opportunity to open up White's kingside within the next few moves. How can they accomplish this and gain a long-term advantage?} 21... f4 $1 {[%cal Gf4g3] First, we begin by attacking the knight on [g3].} 22. Nf1 f3 {[%cal Gf3g2] Now the pawn advances further into White's kingside in order to create a king safety problem. If the pawn on [g2] disappears, then White's king will be more exposed.} 23. Ng3 $2 {White reactivates the knight but allows us to crack open their kingside structure.} (23. g3 {would have been a better defense for White but still runs into problems.} Qh5 $1 {Attacking the pawn on [e5]. White cannot defend it without causing themselves trouble.} 24. Qe3 $4 Qh3 {-+ and now we see the problem for White. The queen is taking away the [e3]-square for White's knight and White cannot prevent checkmate without giving up the queen on [f3].}) 23... fxg2 $19 {We have been able to weaken White's kingside considerably and can start maneuvering our pieces to attack next.} *

