[GameId "2133654360447001"]

{White's king is very weak now. Aside from the king safety problem, they also have an isolated h-pawn and backward f-pawn. How can Black look to maneuver pieces to join in the attack?} 24... Rf4 $1 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ga8f8] Preparing to double the rooks on the f-file and target the [f2]-pawn, which is the first focal point in Black's attack.} 25. Re3 Raf8 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf8f2]} 26. Rf1 Qg5 {[%csl Re5,Rg3][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gc6e5] Threatening the e-pawn and looking to play ...[h5]-[h4] to attack White's pinned knight.} 27. Qe2 {Covering both the pawn on [e5] and the [h5]-square.} Be8 $1 {[%cal Gh7h5] Preventing White from playing [Qh5], which would offer a queen trade. This is something Black has zero desire to do when White's king is so exposed! The bishop also enables Black to play ...[h5] on the next move.} 28. h3 h5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh5h4]} 29. Kh2 h4 30. Nh1 Bh5 {Black's pieces continue flooding the kingside.} 31. Qe1 d4 {If the pawn is traded on [d4], then the knight also gets to join the attack.} 32. Rg1 Rxf2+ {Black calculates an opportunity to win material.} 33. Nxf2 Qf4+ 34. Kh1 dxe3 {With an extra pawn and a raging attack, Black is clearly winning here.} 35. Ng4 Bxg4 36. Rxg4 Qf3+ 37. Kg1 Nxe5 38. Rd4 Qxh3 39. Be2 Rf2 {[%csl Rg1] White resigned since checkmate is incoming. Black did a very nice job of cracking open White's kingside and then taking advantage of White's long-term king safety problem.} 0-1

