{In this opposite-side castling position, both sides are looking to attack the opponent's king. White has just played 26.f6 , looking to open our kingside up. How should we play in response?} 26... b3 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb3c2,Ge4c2,Gc8c2,Gb8b2] We also make a pawn break to open up lines toward our opponent's king! The [c2]-pawn is the focal point of our attack since it's being hit by the bishop, rook, and b-pawn.} 27. axb3 Bxc2+ $1 {Capturing with the rook would also work, but this is a bit simpler since we're not sacrificing as much material. It also comes with check so it's more forcing!} 28. Ka1 {White decides to give up the exchange rather than allow our queen to capture on [b3].} ({After} 28. Nxc2 Qxb3 {, White cannot defend against ...[Qxb2]# and ...[Qxc2]+ at the same time.} 29. Qa3 Qxc2+ {+ -+ and we're ahead a pawn with a very dangerous attack.}) 28... Bxd1 $19 {We will be ahead an exchange with a huge advantage.} *

