{White's king continues to be exposed. Can you finish things off?} 31... Qa5+ {This leads to a forced checkmate sequence but requires precise calculation.} (31... Qxd7 {-+ , trading queens still leads to a large advantage for Black, but you miss the chance to win the game much quicker.}) 32. Kb1 Rxb2+ $1 33. Kxb2 Qb4+ $1 {We need to keep using the queen to give checks first. Checking with the rook on [b8] would allow White's king to run towards the center of the board.} (33... Rb8+ $4 {The wrong check! Following} 34. Kc2 Qa2+ 35. Kd3 Rb3+ 36. Ke4 Qe2+ 37. Kf4 Qe3+ 38. Kg4 Qe4+ 39. Kg3 Qxe5+ 40. Kf2 Qe3+ 41. Kf1 {± , White's king has managed to run away and avoid checks.}) 34. Ka1 Qa3+ {Inching closer to the king.} 35. Kb1 Rb8+ {Now checking on the b-file works since White's king will not be able to run to [d3] anymore.} 36. Kc2 Rb2+ {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ga3c3,Ga3a1] White resigned. After the king moves to [c1], you can checkmate with the queen on [a1] or [c3].} 0-1

