{Black has just played 29...exf4 . What is the drawback of this move, and how can White take advantage of the opportunity?} 30. Qb2 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb2g7] Ignoring the pawn on [f4] and focusing instead on attacking the king! The capture 29...exf4 opened up the long diagonal for White's [a1]-bishop and gave White the chance to use it to attack. Unfortunately, White missed this idea in the game.} (30. gxf4 {± − in the game, White missed this opportunity but still got a strong attack later anyways. The next trainable is from a later position in the same game.}) 30... Bf8 {Black defends the [g7]-pawn and appears safe at first glance. However...} (30... Be5 {, blocking the diagonal doesn't work as long as we don't let our rook on [d1] get captured:} 31. Rxd8+ Qxd8 32. Nxe5 {+- .}) 31. Rxd8 ({Checking right away would also work:} 31. Nh6+ Kh8 32. Rxd8 Nxd8 33. Bxa8 {+- , and we're ahead a piece with a winning advantage.}) 31... Qxd8 ({After} 31... Nxd8 32. Bxa8 {+- , we end up ahead a piece.}) 32. Nh6+ $1 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Ga1h8] Taking advantage of the pin on Black's [g7]-pawn.} Kh8 (32... gxh6 33. Qh8#) 33. Nxf7+ $18 {[%csl Rd8,Rh8][%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8] We win the queen and the game.} *

