{White has just played 15.f4, attacking our knight on [e5]. How should Black respond?} 15... hxg3 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gg3h2,Gg3f2] Ignoring White's threat and instead installing a strong pawn on [g3], which will help with a kingside attack.} 16. fxe5 Qh4 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gh4h2] Threatening checkmate on [h2].} 17. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gf3h2] Covering the [h2]-square and attacking the queen.} Qh6 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gh6e3] Retreating to [h6] is the most precise move, as it puts pressure on the [e3]-pawn.} 18. Qd2 {Defending the [e3]-pawn.} (18. exd6 $2 {This greedy move by White would lead to a quick loss.} Qxe3+ 19. Kh1 Qh6+ 20. Kg1 Bd4+ $1 {The knight cannot capture the bishop since it needs to continue covering the [h2]-square.} 21. Qxd4 cxd4 {-+ and Black is ahead a queen against two minor pieces with a huge advantage.}) 18... Bxe5 $19 {Black decides to recapture the pawn and activate the bishop. The attack against White's kingside is not going to disappear anytime soon due to the structural problem. This is a long-term king safety issue, not a short-term one!} ({Developing the light-squared bishop and threatening to capture on f3 would also be a good way to continue the attack:} 18... Bg4 {-+ . Black plays this move later in the game.}) *

