{How can Black continue the attack from here?} 19... Bg4 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gg4f3,Gh6h2] Threatening to capture the knight and then invade the [h2]-square with checkmate soon.} 20. Rfe1 {White frees up the [f1]-square for the king to run away to.} Rae8 {Bringing another piece into the attack. The rook can help to target the e-pawn and play down the e-file.} (20... Bxf3 $2 {It is too early to capture the knight. After} 21. Bxf3 Qh2+ 22. Kf1 {⩲ , the king is escaping, and White is still ahead in material.}) 21. a6 Bf4 $1 {Black aims to open the e-file so that White's king has a harder time running away from the kingside.} 22. Nd1 {Protecting the [e3]-pawn, but this doesn't help much.} (22. exf4 Bxf3 23. Bxf3 Qh2+ 24. Kf1 Qh1# {and now we see the benefit of the rook! The [e2]-square is covered and White is checkmated.}) 22... Rxe3 $1 {White resigned. The attack on White's kingside is too strong, and Black's pieces are too active to be dealt with.} 0-1

