{Carlsen's opponent missed a golden opportunity to create a weakness in White's position. How should Black play?} 16... Bxf3 $1 {This capture will either result in Black winning a pawn or opening up White's kingside, creating a king safety advantage for Black.} (16... Ba6 $6 {was played in the game. Following} 17. Ne5 {⩲ , White does not end up with any clear weaknesses and is doing fine.}) 17. gxf3 {White may decide to avoid losing a pawn, but White's king is now very exposed, and the kingside pawn structure is in ruins. What is the best way for Black to take advantage of these things?} (17. Qxf3 {loses the [c4]-pawn but at least keeps the kingside protection intact.} Rxc4 {∓ and Black is ahead by a pawn with a solid advantage. White is also left with the isolated d-pawn.}) 17... Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gd8h4,Gh5f4] Attacking the [h4]-pawn and targeting the weak [f4]-square.} 18. Qe4 {[%csl Rh7] The only way for White to defend the [h4]-pawn. This also threatens checkmate on [h7].} f5 {Blocking the checkmate threat and kicking the queen backwards.} 19. Qe3 Qxh4 $19 {[%csl Rg1,Rc4][%cal Gf8d6] Black is ahead a pawn with a very large advantage. White is going to face a strong attack with ...[Bd6] coming up, and will have trouble defending the kingside. Note that the [c4]-pawn is also hanging and Black may decide to capture that at any time.} *

