[GameId "2133654360692780"]

{The definition of a material advantage is pretty straightforward: It is when you have a higher point count of material than your opponent. You may be ahead one or more pawns, a minor piece, an exchange (rook vs. opponent's minor piece) , a rook, or a queen. Whatever difference of material there is between yourself and your opponent, this will constitute a material advantage. If the material count is equal between you and your opponent, then this advantage does not exist. In the position on the board, White is ahead a knight but behind two pawns. Since a knight is generally worth three points and pawns are worth one, this means that White is ahead by one point in material. You can see how the game continued by clicking here.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Material Advantage"]
[Black "Material − How to Gain this Advantage"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654360717357"]

{There are a few ways to gain this advantage: Capturing free material due to opponent's mistake or blunder. Executing a tactic. Accepting a sacrifice from the opponent opening gambit or if they willingly gave up material later in the game.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Material Advantage"]
[Black "Material − Blueprint to Convert"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654360819758"]

{Once we've gained a material advantage, then there tend to be two main plans. The first one is to simplify the position by trading pieces with the goal of getting to the endgame where the material advantage will be more felt. The reason that material advantage is more pronounced in the endgame is due to the reduced amount of pieces on the board. A useful analogy I like to use is the game of basketball. If one team has 5 players and the other team has 4 players, then the team with more players has better chances of winning since the opponents are outnumbered. It is more likely that one player will be left unguarded and be able to score. However, it is still possible for the team with 4 players to win if they are better than their opponents. On the other hand, if you take off one player per team a few times then the matchup goes from 5 vs. 4 to 4 vs. 3, 3 vs. 2, 2 vs. 1, and eventually 1 vs. 0. It is impossible to lose when you have no opponent! It's the same way with chess. If you are ahead a piece, but there are still a lot of pieces on the board for both players, then you could still make a mistake and lose, or your opponent could happen to outplay you and win. In the endgame though, with less pieces on the board, it becomes less likely you'll make a blunder since the positions are less 'noisy' and more likely you'll be able to win with your extra material. This is especially the case if you can trade off the queens, as then you will significantly reduce the position's complexity, making it easier for us to convert our long-term material advantage. Another thing to note is that if you're only ahead a pawn rather than a piece, it can be very good to work towards creating a passed pawn if you don't already have one. A passed pawn can be very annoying for the opponent to deal with, especially if there are other problems for the opponent on the board as well. The blueprint looks like this: ➝ Gain material advantage ➝ Trade pieces (especially queens) ➝ Create a passed pawn ➝ Get to the endgame phase ➝ Use extra material to win the endgame. The blueprint for this specific advantage is probably the most common one that students are familiar with: 'If you're ahead in material, then trade pieces.' In addition, there is also a second plan of converting a material advantage. This one is less well-known, but it is to make use of your extra material and attack the opponent's king. Your extra material (especially if it is an extra piece) acts as extra 'firepower' that you can use to attack. If your opponent has 2 minor pieces and you have 3, you may be able to leverage that extra minor piece to launch a stronger attack, resulting in your opponent being outnumbered. This way of converting a material advantage tends to be more common when it is an extra piece. If you're only ahead by a pawn, then it's unlikely that the single extra pawn will contribute to any significant attack, and you may want to refer to the first plan above for converting that smaller material advantage. The blueprint looks like this: ➝ Gain material advantage ➝ Use extra piece/firepower to attack opponent's king ➝ Gain more advantage or checkmate opponent's king. Let's move on to a few examples where we will see these blueprints in action.} 1. Z0 *

