[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "q3r1k1/p2n1ppp/bp3n2/3p4/P2P4/B3P3/5PPP/R2QK1NR w KQ - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "13"]
[GameId "2133654360877106"]

{White is ahead an exchange, but what should we do next? Well, despite being ahead material, there are still some problems to solve in our position: we're not developed well and haven't castled yet. How do we fix these problems?} 15. Ne2 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Ga6f1,Ge1g1] Developing the knight while also blocking off the bishop's diagonal towards the [f1]-square. This means that we will be able to castle kingside soon.} (15. Nf3 {∞ develops the knight but doesn't block the [a6]-bishop, which means we will still have trouble castling.}) 15... Qb8 {It's always important to ask ourselves why our opponent played their most recent move or what their idea is, especially if we already have a long-term advantage and don't want it to disappear! What do you think is Black's idea behind ...[Qb8]?} 16. h3 $1 {A very important move showing good prophylaxis. White prevents Black from playing their idea of ...[Ng4]. Next, we can castle kingside with much less trouble to worry about.} (16. O-O $2 {is a good example of a common mistake: focusing on your own ideas and not considering the opponent's ideas. We get to castle our king but don't think about what Black might do in response!} Ng4 {∞ and all of a sudden we're in a tricky situation. Black is threatening ...[Qxh2]# and any way that we defend against this will have drawbacks. Blocking the diagonal with the knight loses the rook on [f1], and pushing [g3] weakens the light squares around our king and gives Black more counterplay.}) 16... Bc4 17. O-O {Now we're much safer than before.} a6 18. Re1 {Breaking the pin so that the knight can move around.} b5 {This pawn break only helps White. This is because when you're ahead an exchange rook vs. minor piece then you usually want to work towards trading pawns to open files for the extra rook that you have. Here Black is making our job easier with this pawn break.} 19. axb5 axb5 {Now our [a1]-rook has an open file to work with. Again though, it is still important to ask ourselves: what does the opponent want to do with their next move?} 20. Bb4 $1 {Blockading Black's passed b-pawn. We don't want it to advance too far down the board and become a headache for us.} Ne4 21. f3 $18 {Kicking back the knight but also slightly weakening the kingside. White continues to maintain the material advantage with a strong position.} (21. Ra3 Ndf6 22. Qc2 h5 23. Rea1 {+- may have been a slightly more precise way to play. We double rooks on the open a-file and then invade into Black's position next. ♔ Remember: When you're ahead material, you have to make use of that extra material! Whether it is an extra pawn, minor piece, exchange, etc., you have to put that extra material to good use.}) *

