{Should White trade pieces on [d6]?} 22. Ng3 {No! White should keep the bishop on [b4] where it is performing an important role of blockading Black's passed b-pawn. Also, with the move ...[Nd6], Black was opening up the rook to attack our [e3]-pawn. So by playing [Ng3], we are opening up our [e1]-rook to defend that pawn.} (22. Bxd6 {+- , usually when you're ahead material you want to trade pieces, but here our bishop had a very important job of blockading the b-pawn. White is still better after this trade, but there is no additional benefit to trade off this important piece.}) 22... Nf6 23. Ra6 Nde4 $5 {Black tries to muddy the game by playing this 'sacrifice'.} 24. Nf5 {[%cal Gf3e4] White decided to avoid any trouble connected with allowing ...[Qxg3]. Now the knight on [e4] is legitimately hanging.} (24. fxe4 $5 {is fine to play too but does require a precise continuation.} Qxg3 25. e5 $1 {White needs to keep the center of the board locked up. ( After 25.exd5? Bxd5 ∞ , Black has more counterplay here due to the pressure on our kingside. )} Ne4 26. Qf3 {+- , defending the [f2]-square and offering a queen trade. White is firmly in the driver's seat.}) 24... Ng5 25. Qd2 $18 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ge3e4,Ge1a1] Keeping everything safe. Playing [e4] with a discovered attack on the [g5]-knight might also be an idea. Doubling up the rooks on the a-file is good to do next too.} *

