{Black is forking our rook on [a6] and knight on [f5]. How should we respond?} 26. Rxf6 {[%csl Ra6,Rf5][%cal Gc8a6,Gc8f5] This is a little simplification 'tactic'. White is not winning material but is using forcing moves to trade off a few pieces, which is very favorable for them since we're ahead material in the first place.} (26. Ne7+ $4 {would be a big mistake and allow Black to win a piece:} Rxe7 27. Bxe7 Qxa6 {∓ . All of a sudden it is Black who has two minor pieces vs. our rook and they have the advantage now.}) 26... gxf6 27. Nd6 Qb8 28. Nxe8 Qxe8 {White has been able to trade a few pieces and with the reduced material it is easier to convert the advantage due to less counterplay that Black can create.} 29. Qf2 Qa8 30. Qg3 Qa4 31. Qd6 Qc2 32. Qf8# {White did a very nice job in this game. First, they won the exchange with the bishop attacks. Second, they prioritized their own goals: developing and castling while also not ignoring the opponent's ideas ...[Ng4] and working against them h3. Finally, they mobilized their pieces and were able to execute a simplification sequence that made the game easier to convert.} 1-0

