{Black is ahead one pawn but has to deal with White's threat on their knight. How should Black respond?} 18... Bf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6d4] Rather than passively defending against the threat, Black instead counterattacks White's [d4]-bishop and guarantees a trade of pieces.} 19. Bxf6 {White goes for the trade, which allows Black to simplify the position further.} (19. Qxg4 $2 {Not only does this allow an easy trade of pieces, but it gives Black the bishop pair and loses the [e4]-pawn.} Bxd4+ 20. Kh1 Bxe4 {-+ , Black has a very large advantage with two extra pawns and the bishop pair.}) (19. e5 $5 {is White's trickiest response to our counterattack. However, this will still end in a position where Black is having a big advantage.} dxe5 {, not only capturing the pawn but also opening up the queen to attack the bishop on [d4].} 20. Bc5 {, Black now has two pieces attacked at the same time with the knight and rook both being hit.} e4 {, continuing to answer White's threats with our own attacks in response.} 21. Bxf8 exd3 22. Qxg4 Qd4+ 23. Kh1 Rxf8 {-+ and Black ends up having a bishop plus two pawns for a rook. This alone is a case of equal material count but on top of that, Black has a passed d-pawn and strong pressure along the bishops' diagonals.}) 19... Nxf6 {[%csl Re4] Now the pawn on [e4] is attacked.} 20. e5 dxe5 21. fxe5 Qd4+ $19 {Centralizing the queen with a gain of time due to the check. Black continues to have a big advantage due to their material and piece activity.} *

