{Black's knight on [f6] continues to be under attack. How should Black react?} 22... Qe4 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge4e2] Instead of reacting to White's threat on our knight, Black responds with another threat of their own! This time we're offering a queen trade, which would continue to simplify the position when we're ahead a pawn.} ({There was nothing wrong with moving the knight to safety too:} 22... Ne4 {-+ .}) 23. Qf2 {White avoids the trade but walks into further trouble.} (23. Qxe4 Nxe4 {-+ , the trade of queens on [e4] would allow Black to save their knight and end up ahead a pawn with no counterplay for White.}) 23... Ng4 24. Qg3 Ne3 {[%csl Rd3,Rf1,Rg2][%cal Ge3f1,Ge4d3,Ge4g2] White cannot save both the knight and [f1]-rook and deal with the attack on the [g2]-pawn at the same time.} 25. Rg1 Qxd3 26. Rae1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gg3d3,Ge1e3] White tries to take advantage of the knight on [e3] being pinned to the queen.} Nxg2 $1 {[%csl Re1,Rh1][%cal Gg2e1,Gb7h1] Another tactic! Black is able to leave their queen hanging due to the idea of ...[Nxe1]+ followed by ...[Nxd3]. White ended up resigning here since they are going to be down material with no compensation at all.} 0-1

