{Black is ahead one pawn and has the option to exchange pieces. Should Black play Bxf3 or something else?} 18... Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rd3,Rd5][%cal Gb4d5,Gb4d3] This is a much better way to exchange pieces. Instead of trading off our only bishop, we are able to eliminate one of White's two bishops while also simplifying the position.} (18... Bxf3 $2 {The wrong trade!} 19. Bxf3 {, it is true that Black has traded a pair of pieces and this is usually good when you're ahead material. However, now White has the pair of bishops against Black's pair of knights and the position is much trickier for Black to convert into a win due to this increased compensation for White. Also, the [d4]-pawn is not free to capture.} Nxd4 $6 20. Bxb7 {± and White is still down one pawn but will capture the [a6]-pawn next, which will erase Black's material advantage. The only one who will be left with an advantage afterwards is White due to their bishop pair.}) 19. Qb3 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 c6 {The best way to deal with White's threat on the [b7]-pawn. Black continues to have an extra pawn in the position and is well on their way to converting their advantage as the game progresses.} *

