{Black has just played ...[g5], attacking our knight. How should we respond?} 24. Nxd5 $1 {We can capture the pawn on [d5] due to tactics working in our favor.} Nxd5 {There are many different move orders and sequences that work for White to come out ahead at least one pawn. Each of them focuses on attacking the pinned knight/bishop on the d-file using the rook, queen, and e-pawn.} ({Capturing with the bishop runs into similar problems to the main line:} 24... Bxd5 25. Bxd5 Nxd5 26. Qd2 Rd8 27. e4 Qf6 28. exd5 {+- .}) 25. Bxd5 {Other moves like [Qb3], [Qd2], [Qd3], [Qf5] would also work. Note that [e4] doesn't work though!} (25. e4 $4 {We cannot use the e-pawn yet since Black has defensive resources involving our undefended queen on [c2].} Qc7 {-+ , Black gets away from the pin and counterattacks our queen. We will not be able to win the piece back now and will be down in material.}) 25... Bxd5 26. Qd2 {Playing [Qd3] would also work. However, you must not play [Qf5] in this position!} (26. Qf5 $4 {This square doesn't work anymore!} Be4 $1 {Black breaks the pin and counterattacks our queen. After} 27. Qxg5+ Qg6 {-+ , Black saves their queen and keeps their extra piece.}) 26... Rd8 ({In the game, Black moved away from the pin and allowed White to win the piece back immediately:} 26... Qf6 27. Qxd5 {+- . White has an extra pawn and went on to win the game later.}) 27. e4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge4d5,Gd1d6] Using the e-pawn is necessary if Black devotes everything to defending the bishop.} Qf6 28. exd5 $18 {We end up being ahead a clean pawn.} *

