{Earlier White had given Black a pawn weakness and now has finally captured the pawn to gain a material advantage. Next, the goal is to work towards converting the new material advantage.} 29. Re5 {Pinning the knight, which will lead to eventual piece trades.} Nf8 30. Rxe8 {Now a pair of rooks is traded.} Rxe8 31. d5 {White has an extra passed d-pawn and starts to march it forward.} Qe5 32. d6 Nd7 33. h3 {Freeing up the [h2]-square so that there is no longer any need to worry about back-rank checkmates.} Re6 34. f4 Qe3 35. Qxe3 (35. Qd5 {+- , keeping the queens on the board would have been more precise. The reason is that Black's king is weaker and by keeping the queen on the board we can use it to attack as well as help to attack the knight on [d7] that is blockading our passed d-pawn.}) 35... Rxe3 36. Nd5 $18 {Carlsen went on to later convert the endgame with his extra pawn into a win.} 1-0

