{Black has the opportunity to win material. How can they accomplish this?} 10... Nxg5 {Black begins a series of captures that will leave them ahead a pawn.} (10... cxd4 {-+ , capturing on [d4] first will most likely transpose.}) 11. Nxg5 cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ga5g5] This opens a discovered attack towards White's knight.} 13. Ne4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1c4]} b5 $19 {Defending the [c4]-pawn. There is no need to worry about the check on [d6] since our king will be safe on the [e7]-square. Black is ahead one pawn with a healthy advantage.} ({After} 13... Qxa3 $6 14. Bxc4 {∓ , Black is still ahead a pawn and better, but we don't need to allow White's bishop to get activated so easily.}) (13... Qc7 $2 {defends the pawn and [d6]-square, but the queen is overloaded.} 14. Bxc4 {∞ , White can grab the pawn and equalize material since capturing on [c4] would walk into a fork on [d6].}) *

