{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 12... Bb4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb4e1] White has trouble defending the [c4]-pawn due to the pin.} 13. b3 {This defends the pawn but allows a fork tactic.} (13. O-O {unpins the knight but leaves the [c4]-pawn underprotected.} Bxd2 {, eliminating one of the defenders of [c4].} 14. Bxd2 Bxc4 {∓ and we're ahead a pawn with a good advantage. We'll trade the light-squared bishops next.}) 13... Bc3 {[%csl Ra1,Re5][%cal Gc3a1,Gc3e5] Both the rook and [e5]-pawn are hit. White cannot avoid losing material.} 14. Rb1 Qxe5 $15 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge5e1] Capturing with the queen is best since we want to trade queens, when we're ahead material. Black has a pleasant advantage with the extra pawn.} (14... Bxe5 $6 {is not as precise since we cannot guarantee a queen trade anymore.} 15. O-O {⩲ and White has compensation with the queens on the board since they may be able to attack our king who has trouble castling. If we castle kingside, we get checkmated on [h7], while if we castle queenside, then [c5] could be a problem for us.}) *

