{A bishop pair advantage is one where you have two bishops and your opponent has one or zero bishops. This kind of situation is generally considered an advantage for the player with the two bishops because a pair of bishops can potentially control all 64 squares on the board (32 light squares + 32 dark squares) while the player who has only one bishop will have less control of the opposite color of their bishop. For example: If they own a light-squared bishop but no dark-squared bishop then they will have a harder time fighting on the dark squares. If a player has two bishops vs. the opponent's zero bishops, then this advantage is magnified. In the position on the board, we can see that Black has the bishop pair the dark-squared bishop on [f8] and the light-squared bishop on [f5] while White only has one bishop the light-squared bishop on [f1]. This means that Black has a long-term advantage in this position due to owning the bishop pair. You can see how the game continued by clicking here.} 10... Z0 *

