{There are a few ways to gain this advantage: Actively look to trade one of your knights for one of the opponent's bishops. Your opponent willingly traded off one of their bishops for one of your knights. Sometimes it can be useful to sacrifice the exchange our rook for an opponent’s minor piece to gain the bishop pair.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Bishop Pair"]
[Black "Bishop Pair − Blueprint to Convert"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654361233491"]

{Once we've gained the bishop pair advantage, there are two plans to work towards. The first main plan is to work towards opening the position. An open position is one where there are few pawns on the board. Bishops like open positions because they are long-range pieces. The more pawns on the board, the more the bishops will be blocked in or blunted. If you compare a position where all 8 pawns are on the board to a position where there are 3 pawns on the board, then the bishops would be much happier in the position with less pawns. The more pawns there are, the more 'closed' the windows are in front of the bishops. Bishops can be active from afar. A bishop can be on [h1] but target straight into the opponent's queenside, hitting squares like [c6], [b7], and [a8] if there are no pawns in the way. On the other hand, knights don't mind there being plenty of pawns on the board since they are short-range pieces and like to sit on active outposts where they are supported by a pawn. If we have the bishop pair advantage, then it is likely that our opponent has more knights than we do. So how do we open a position? In order to do this we are going to want to trade one or more of our pawns with our opponent's pawns. If we cannot immediately trade pawns, then we must work towards pawn breaks. A pawn break is a move where we advance one of our pawns to a square that challenges an enemy pawn. The goal with a pawn break is to advance our pawn and then trade off the pair of pawns (ours and the opponents) so that there is one less pair of pawns on the board. ♔ Remember: The less pawns on the board, the happier our bishops will be! The blueprint looks like this: ➝ Trade off one of your knights for one of your opponent's bishops to gain the bishop pair advantage ➝ Trade pawns to open the position ➝ If no pawn trades are available then look for pawn breaks ➝ As the position opens up, the bishops will be better than the opponent's knights. A second plan that we can consider when we have the bishop pair advantage is to focus our play around the color of the bishop that we have but our opponent does not. For example, if we have a dark-squared bishop and our opponent doesn't, then we have more firepower on the dark squares. Even though knights can control both light and dark squares, it is important to recognize that they must alternate between the two colors as they move and are not as efficient as bishops at controlling a specific color. The blueprint looks like this: ➝ Trade off one of your knights for one of your opponent's bishops to gain the bishop pair advantage ➝ Focus your play around the color that your opponent doesn't have a bishop for. Let's move on to a few examples where we will see these blueprints in action.} 1. Z0 *

