[PlyCount "15"]
[GameId "2133654361249876"]

{We pick up this game during the opening phase. The game started with a London System characterized by White's bishop on [f4]. How can Black gain the bishop pair advantage from here?} 8... Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gh5f4] Hunting the London bishop down.} 9. Bg3 (9. Bg5 $6 {Moving the bishop here doesn't save the bishop for long and only helps Black to gain a bigger space advantage:} f6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 e5 {∓ . Black has gained the bishop pair advantage anyway but also got a bigger space advantage along the way. Even if White trades pawns on [e5] and captures the [g5]-pawn, we can play ...[Rg8] followed by castling queenside. We will have a big center, the bishop pair, and a safer king, while White's development and piece coordination are nonexistent. All for the price of only one pawn, which is well worth it for us!}) 9... Nxg3 10. hxg3 {Now that we have the bishop pair advantage, the next step is to continue developing the pieces and work towards opening the center of the board so that the bishops are happier.} g6 11. Nbd2 h5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg7h6] Gaining some space on the kingside. The bishop may develop to [h6] or [g7] depending on the situation.} 12. b3 {White breaks against our [c4]-pawn, but this allows us to trade more pawns and open the position bit by bit.} cxb3 13. axb3 Rc8 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc6b4,Gb4c2] Lining up towards the queen. There are now ideas of ...[Nb4]-[c2].} 14. Qb2 Bg7 {[%csl Ra1,Rb2][%cal Gg7a1] The bishop lines up towards the queen and rook on the diagonal. It may seem like these pieces are far off and there are two pawns in the way on the diagonal, but we'll see the power of the bishop as the game progresses.} 15. Nh4 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gh4f5] White attacks one of our bishops. We don't want to let them get rid of our strategic advantage so easily.} Bg4 $19 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gg4d1,Gg7a1] The bishop is actively placed here and makes it less desirable for White to play [Be2]. Next, we want to play ...[e5] as a central pawn break in order to open the center of the board for our bishop pair.} (15... Bd7 $6 {The bishop is unnecessarily passive here. After} 16. Be2 {∓ , Black still has the advantage, but it's not as large since White has been able to activate their light-squared bishop while ours is less useful.}) *

