[FEN "2r1k2r/pp2ppb1/1qn3p1/3p3p/3P1PbN/1PP1P1P1/1Q1N2P1/R3KB1R b KQk - 0 16"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2133654361262165"]

{White has just played [f4] which gave them a bigger grip on the [e5]-square. How should we continue from here to make use of our bishop pair?} 16... e5 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gb6e3] We wanted to play ...[e5] in order to open diagonals for our bishops especially the [g7]-bishop that was blocked in by the [d4]-pawn, but it looked like White had stopped our idea. With the use of calculation, we can still make our desirable ...[e5] pawn break happen anyway! Whenever you have a strategically desirable move that doesn't look like it works tactically at first glance, an important question to ask yourself is: 'What if I play it anyways?' I know this as the 'Shankland Rule' and it works out brilliantly here!} 17. Nhf3 {White decides to get their knight closer to the center and not take the [e5]-pawn.} (17. dxe5 $4 {The [d4]-pawn needs to stay in place to block the diagonal of Black's queen.} Qxe3+ 18. Be2 Qxe2#) (17. fxe5 Bxe5 {, threatening checkmate on [g3].} 18. Kf2 (18. dxe5 $4 Qxe3+ {+ -+}) 18... Bb8 {-+ , White is in huge trouble because their king is very exposed and our bishops are slicing through their position. The [g3]-pawn is the next target with ...[Qc7] coming soon.}) 17... O-O {There is no rush to trade pawns on [f4] or [d4] yet since the [e5]-pawn still cannot be captured for free. By keeping the pawn on [e5] a bit longer we prevent White from developing their bishop to [d3].} 18. Be2 {[%cal Gf4e5] White develops their bishop and is now legitimately threatening to capture the [e5]-pawn.} (18. Bd3 $4 {walks into a fork since our e-pawn is still on the board:} e4 {-+ .}) (18. fxe5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Qxe3+ 20. Be2 Bxe5 {-+ and White cannot deal with all of Black's threats. The [g3] and [c3]-pawns are both attacked and White's king will never find safety. White cannot capture on [e5] due to checkmate on [e2].}) 18... exd4 $19 {The best way to trade pawns since it guarantees that either the e-file or c-file will open up. The bishops are happy about the pawn trade and the rooks will be happy too!} *

