{We've been able to open the position by trading off the e-pawns. What is the next step?} 19... Rfe8 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge8e1] Pinning the bishop means that White cannot castle their king to safety.} 20. Kf1 ({The f2-square is mined:} 20. Kf2 Nxd4 $1 21. cxd4 Bxd4+ 22. Qxd4 Rxe2+ {would be bad news for White. The rook is taboo, while after} 23. Kg1 Qxd4+ 24. Nxd4 Rxd2 {, the endgame is dead lost.}) 20... Re3 {[%csl Rc3,Rg3][%cal Gc8e8] Putting some pressure on the [c3]-pawn and preparing to double rooks on the e-file.} 21. Rc1 Ne7 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Ge7f5,Gf5g3] Maneuvering the knight towards [f5] where it will attack the [g3]-pawn.} 22. Nb1 Nf5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gf5g3]} 23. Kf2 Rce8 {All of Black's pieces are incredibly active and the final blow will come soon.} 24. Bd1 Bxf3 {Eliminating the knight that was defending the [d4]-pawn.} 25. gxf3 Nxd4 {[%csl Rb2,Rf2][%cal Gg7b2,Gg7d4,Gd4f2] White resigned here since capturing the knight would be met with ...[Bxd4] where the queen would be attacked as well as discovered checks towards White's king. This game showed very nice play where after gaining the bishop pair the consistent goal was to open the position with pawn breaks and trades so that the bishops became better and better. It's fitting that the final tactic uses both bishops ...[Bxf3] and a later ...[Bxd4].} 0-1

