{How can White work towards opening diagonals for the bishop pair?} 32. Rh1 $1 {[%cal Gh3h4] Planning to make the [h4] pawn break. This will result in opening the h-file, which will become dangerous for Black.} (32. cxd5 $6 {Trading pawns is usually good for the player with the bishop pair, but the downside here is that there are no more easy pawn breaks after the trade in the center.} exd5 {, Black has opened their [e8]-rook and White hasn't gained as much as they would like.}) (32. e4 $2 {This pawn break does open more lines but weakens the [d4]-pawn and [f4]-square at the same time.} dxc4 {, White cannot recapture with their b-pawn due to losing the [d4]-pawn.} 33. Bxc4 {, defending the [d4]-pawn.} Ne7 {∓ , the knight maneuvers to the [g6] and [f4]-squares next. White will regreat weakening the [f4]-square once the knight gets there.}) (32. b4 $2 {Trying to work towards a pawn break on [b5] but this leads to the bishop on [a5] being trapped:} b6 {-+ .}) 32... g6 $6 {This does nothing to stop White's plan.} (32... Bc7 $1 {was Black's best move. The idea is not only to offer a bishop trade, but if White declines the trade and retreats the bishop, then Black can play ...[Bd8], which would prevent the [h4] pawn break.} 33. Bxc7 Rxc7 34. h4 gxh4 35. Rxh4 {⩲ and White is still a bit better off with the bishop vs. knight imbalance.}) 33. h4 gxh4 34. Rxh4 $16 {[%cal Gc1h1] White has been able to open the position a bit more and will double up the rooks on the h-file soon.} *

