{There are still seven pawns per side. How can White look for a pawn break that helps to open the position for their bishop pair?} 27. b4 $1 {Looking to trade pawns to open the position.} cxb4 $2 {Trading pawns gets Black into huge trouble.} ({In the game, Black retreated the knight immediately since capturing the pawn would have been bad:} 27... Nc6 28. bxc5 bxc5 $2 {This recapture was bad and left Black with a worse pawn structure due to the isolated c-pawn.} 29. Nc4 {± and White went on to win the game later.}) 28. cxb4 {Attacking the knight once again.} Nc6 (28... Qc6 {, trying to trade queens doesn't help Black. After} 29. Qd1 {+- , the knight on [a5] is trapped and White wins material.}) 29. Rac1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc1c8] This pin leads to big problems for Black.} Rc7 30. Nb5 $18 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d4,Gc7d7]} (30. Nb5 {Kicking the rook off c7. After Black plays} Rcd7 {, there are multiple good moves including the simple} 31. Nd4 {, when Black loses material due to the c-file pin.}) *

