{Space on the board is usually defined by who has more pawns along the fourth and fifth ranks; sometimes this includes the third and sixth ranks. Whoever has more pawns across the central two ranks, especially if the pawns have crossed into the opponent's half of the board, will have more control of squares in the position and thus will have a space advantage. If one of your pawns has crossed into the opponent's half of the board, then that pawn may count as more than 1 point since it is cramping the opponent's pieces more than a pawn on your side of the board would be doing. If you think about various openings in chess, you can see how they relate to one player having a space advantage by this definition. A few examples: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Bc5 (. Both players have one pawn on the fourth and fifth ranks, and thus space is equal though White will usually work towards playing [c3]+d4 to gain a space advantage later.) ( 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 − in the French Defense, White starts with a space advantage by having two pawns on the fourth rank compared to their opponent's one pawn on the fifth (rank 2 vs. 1. Sometimes this space advantage can be increased when advancing the e-pawn to [e5].) 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 − same story for the Caro-Kann. ) ( 1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 − White gets a huge space advantage with 4 vs. 1 in the Alekhine Four Pawns Attack variation. ) ( 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 − White starts with a slight 2 vs. 1 space advantage in the Queen's Gambit Declined. ) ( 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Bb4 − in the Nimzo-Indian Defense, White starts with a hefty 2 vs. 0 space advantage, but Black plans to counterattack the center later with ...[c5], ...[d5], or ...[e5] pawn breaks. These are just a few examples, but you can see how a space advantage can be gained from a very early stage in the game based on which opening is played. It also shows that the space control on the board can be affected in the middlegame phase too. There is a constant struggle by both players to battle for space on the board. Usually, it is White who starts with a space advantage in most games (based on having the first move) , but Black will fight back against White's space advantage with pawn breaks a lot of the time. In the position on the board , you can see that White has two pawns on the fourth/fifth ranks (d4+e5) (vs. Black's one pawn on [d5]. White has a 2 vs. 1 advantage, and you could even count the [e5]-pawn as worth more than 1 in this case maybe 1.25. Why is a space advantage good in this case? We can see that due to White's space advantage, it is difficult for Black to activate their pieces. The bishop on [g7] is staring into a well-supported [e5]-pawn, and the knight on [g8] cannot develop to the [f6]-square. On the other hand, White's pieces can develop very easily because the opponent is not controlling as much space and is not limiting White's pieces. You can see how the game continued by clicking here.))} 6... Z0 *

