{There are a few ways to gain this space advantage: From the opening phase some openings give one player more of a space advantage compared to other openings. Advancing your pawns forward while the opponent is not doing the same. Using pawn breaks to exchange off your opponent's pawns and thus lower their space control which, in turn, gives you the advantage.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Space Advantage"]
[Black "Space − Blueprint to Convert"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654361589863"]

{Once we've gained the space advantage, there are two plans to work towards. The first plan is to push the pawns that are giving us the space advantage forward in order to further cramp our opponent. If we can gain a big enough space advantage and roll the pawns into our opponent's territory, then we can really make life difficult for them due to the lack of space. If the opponent is suffocated enough, then it makes the game much easier for us to play due to our mobility advantage. This particular plan is more likely to occur when the central pawns are not locked and are more fluid. In a case like this, it is important to note that the player who has a space advantage should try to avoid trading pieces unless it is necessary or beneficial. Any kind of neutral piece trade is more likely to favor the opponent. This is because the player who is behind in space would really like to reduce the number of pieces on the board so that the remaining pieces are not stepping on each other's toes. The way I think about it is like this: If you live in a big house, then you can fit a family of five people comfortably. On the other hand, if five people live in a studio apartment, then you are all going to be stepping on top of one another. In that case, you would really like to kick out a few of the people, so that you have a bit more space for yourself. Time to send the kids out of the house and off to college! It's also important to understand that regardless of which blueprint you follow, a good opponent will try to make your life difficult. They will attempt to make pawn breaks against your center, break it down, and destroy your space advantage. For this reason, it is very important to work towards securing your space advantage before advancing in the center or maneuvering towards the kingside. If your space advantage isn't stable and your opponent is able to blast open the center, then you may find yourself in trouble when the advantage evaporates! The first blueprint looks like this: ➝ Gain space advantage ➝ Secure the center ➝ Advance fourth/fifth rank pawns further into the opponent's half of the board ➝ Avoid unnecessary or non-beneficial piece trades ➝ Cramp the opponent's pieces heavily and make their life difficult. A second plan to consider when holding a space advantage is to use our piece mobility advantage to maneuver our pieces towards the opponent's king in order to create attacking opportunities. The opponent who is more cramped will have a harder time mobilizing their pieces for defense. A player with a space advantage may be able to transfer pieces from the queenside to the kingside more easily than the player with a space disadvantage! This particular plan is more likely to occur when the center of the board is locked and static. The blueprint looks like this: ➝ Gain space advantage ➝ Secure the center ➝ Avoid unnecessary or non-beneficial piece trades ➝ Make further pawn advances towards the opponent's king and/or maneuver pieces towards the opponent's king to attack. Let's move on to a few examples where we will see these blueprints in action.} 1. Z0 *

