{White has a central space advantage. How can they play to make use of this?} 16. d5 {The knight is kicked backwards, and we can follow up with [e5] next too.} (16. e5 $5 {Advancing the e-pawn is also strong, but not the most precise move order.} dxe5 17. dxe5 Nh5 18. Be4 {+- and White's piece activity advantage is very strong. We can play [Nd5] next to further increase the activity too.}) 16... Na5 {Black has to sideline the knight and either go to [a5] or [b8].} (16... Ne5 $2 {Black immediately blundered in the game by centralizing the knight.} 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. d6 {+- and the bishop is trapped.}) 17. e5 $1 {Continuing to advance forward. This is based on a little tactic, if Black decides to trade pawns.} Ne8 ({After} 17... dxe5 $2 18. d6 {+- , Black's bishop is trapped and we win a piece.}) 18. Bh6 {Our central pawns advancing down the board has forced Black's pieces back to more passive squares. In return, our pieces can move forward!} Ng7 19. e6 fxe6 20. dxe6 Bc6 21. Nd4 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Gc2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge6,Re7,Rg7,Gh6] White has a fantastic position. The piece activity difference is drastic; we have a passed pawn on [e6], and Black's kingside is exposed.} *

