{Here we have a key position to consider. White's game plan revolves around the kingside part of the board, but that doesn't mean we should just completely ignore Black's plan! Black has actually created a positional threat here with their last move ...[Qc7]. What is it, and how can White play against it?} 18. Rac1 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc1c2] Black wanted to play ...[b4] to attack our pawn on [c3] and take advantage of the pin along the c-file. Another option might have been ...[d4] to open the diagonal of the bishop towards the [f3]-knight. By making one safe, prophylactic preventative move with [Rac1], we are looking to stop Black's ideas on the queenside before continuing with our kingside play. Now the bishop on [c2] is defended, which means the [c3]-pawn is no longer pinned.} (18. Rad1 $2 b4 {± , one careless move can make our life more difficult. Now Black is creating counterplay on the queenside based on our [c3]-pawn being pinned, which is annoying for us. White still has the advantage, but there is no need to allow this from Black!}) 18... Ba8 19. Bb1 {White decided to make another safety-first move but will resume the kingside play very soon.} Rb8 20. Nh2 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6][%cal Gh2g4] White is maneuvering the knight towards the [g4]-square where it will not only defend the [e5]-pawn but also threaten to hop into the [f6] or [h6]-squares. White can get away with removing a defender of the [e5]-pawn due to tactical reasons.} Qc4 (20... Nxe5 $2 {Capturing the [e5]-pawn is very risky. After} 21. Qe3 f6 22. hxg6 hxg6 23. Bxg6 {+- , (White's attack is more dangerous than before and the [e5]-knight has trouble getting out of the double pin c7-queen and [b8]-rook.)}) (20... Bxe5 $4 {Capturing with the bishop backfires too.} 21. Bxe5 Nxe5 22. Qf4 $1 {This pin is a problem.} f6 23. Ng4 {+- , Black cannot avoid losing material due to the threat of [Nxf6]+ and then capturing Black's knight.}) 21. b3 {Kicking Black's queen back a bit before attacking on the kingside.} Qc6 22. Ng4 {Continuing to maneuver the knight to a more active location. Here White can ignore Black's idea of ...[d4] since they have a good answer to it.} Rec8 (22... d4 $5 {Black could try this in order to open up the diagonal towards the [g2]-pawn to threaten checkmate.} 23. Be4 {, White blocks off the diagonal and attacks the queen in return. After} Qb6 24. Bxa8 Rxa8 25. cxd4 {+- , White wins a pawn and can continue to attack the kingside next.}) 23. Bh6 $18 {White looks to trade off Black's only defender around the king. The attack will be dangerous to deal with very quickly.} *

