{It's time for White to press forward with their kingside attack. How should they do this?} 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. Qh6+ {Now the final assault on the king starts.} Kg8 26. hxg6 fxg6 27. Bxg6 $1 {These kinds of sacrifices tend to work well when the opponent's pieces are all stuck on the queenside. White breaks through the front door of Black's kingside protection with this sacrifice.} hxg6 28. Qxg6+ Kf8 29. Re3 {White adds more fuel to the fire with this rook lift.} Ke7 30. Qg5+ {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8] Preventing the king from running to [d8].} Ke8 31. Rf3 Qe7 32. Qg8+ Nf8 33. Nf6+ Kd8 34. Nh7 {Black cannot avoid losing material due to the pin.} Qa3 (34... Kc7 35. Rf7 {+- and the king has run into a pin along the 7th rank.}) 35. Rxf8+ {White has won back their sacrificed piece and is easily winning with a material advantage and strong attack.} Kc7 36. Rf7+ Kb6 37. Qg5 Rg8 38. Qe3+ d4 39. Qxd4+ Ka5 40. b4+ Ka4 41. Qd1+ {Black resigned due to checkmate on [b3] next. A masterclass game in regards to converting a space advantage into a win! White first gained the space advantage when the [d4]-pawn moved up to the [e5]-square. Then they secured and overprotected their central [e5]-pawn. Later they built more pressure towards the kingside part of the board, while also being aware of Black's ideas on the queenside. Finally, they crashed through with a strong attack, using the [h5] pawn break and a bishop sacrifice to blast open Black's king protection.} 1-0

