{Black has just played ...[d5], attacking White's [e4]-pawn. How can White gain a bigger space advantage from here?} 6. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rg7,Rg8] This pawn crosses into Black's half of the board and shuts down the [g7]-bishop's diagonal. Also, the [f6]-square is taken away from Black's knight. The kingside pieces start to feel a bit cramped now.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc6e5] Black develops their knight and puts some pressure on the [d4] and [e5]-pawns.} 7. Bb5 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Gb5e8] A simple-looking move but a strong one. The light-squared bishop is not able to help defend the [d4] or [e5]-pawns but can trade itself off for the knight at some point so that there is less pressure on White's center.} (7. Nc3 $2 {Developing the queenside knight allows Black to put more pressure in the center quickly.} Bg4 $1 {Black threatens to capture the knight who is defending the [d4]-pawn.} 8. Bb5 Nh6 {∞ , Black maneuvers the knight towards the [f5]-square, where it will help target White's [d4]-pawn. Our central pawns are both a strength and weakness at the same time! The [d4]-pawn is actually a backward pawn that needs piece protection as the game goes on. For this reason, it's important for us to overprotect these central pawns early in the game so that it's more difficult for Black to attack and break them down.}) 7... Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5] Black looks to maneuver their knight to [f5].} (7... Bg4 {, Black could develop their light-squared bishop here, but we can eliminate one of Black's pieces that can attack our center.} 8. Bxc6+ $1 {Now there is one attacker less on our [d4]-pawn. Also, Black ends up with a pawn weakness on [c6] that we can potentially target later:} bxc6 9. Nbd2 {± . It may look a bit odd to develop our knight in front of the bishop, but the idea here is that if Black takes our [f3]-knight, then we can replace it with our other knight. This means that our central pawns will be more secure.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 $16 {Black didn't rush to put their bishop on [g4], so White finally prevents it from happening. Now our center will feel less pressure since Black's light-squared bishop cannot easily help in the assault on our pawns. By preventing ...[Bg4], we are securing our center more.} *

