{Black has just played ...[a6], attacking our bishop. How should White respond?} 10. Bxc6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b5] This capture breaks the principle of 'avoid piece trades when you have a space advantage', but we have a good reason to make the trade here! White is willing to trade off their bishop for this knight so that there's less pressure on the center and Black ends up with a weak pawn on [c6] too.} bxc6 {[%csl Rc6]} 11. Re1 {Continuing to overprotect the [e5]-pawn.} Bf5 12. Nc3 Qa5 13. Bd2 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gd2a5,Gd1c1] A tricky move to deal with. White not only aims at the queen for a potentially discovered attack but also threatens to play [Qc1], after which Black's knight on [h6] will be trapped. This is the power of a space advantage! Black's pieces are cramped and stepping on each other's toes.} f6 {Black finally attacks White's center a bit and opens the [f7]-square for the knight.} 14. Na4 {Attacking the queen and maneuvering towards the [c5]-square. When one side has a pawn weakness c6, then it is usually a good idea to control the square in front of the pawn and potentially blockade it with a knight.} Qc7 15. Nc5 $18 {[%csl Ge5] White is improving the knight while continuing to keep the [e5]-pawn safe and solid.} *

