{Black is putting a lot of pressure on our [e5]-pawn. How would you respond?} 16. Bf4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf4e5,Gf3e5,Gd4e5,Ge1e5] White continues to protect the center.} (16. e6 $5 {Advancing the pawn forward is an interesting option too.} Nd6 17. Nh4 {+- , Black's bishop on [f5] is running low on squares and the [g7]-bishop is not looking good either.}) (16. exf6 {+- , it's even possible to trade pawns on [f6], but I don't like the look of getting rid of our space advantage.}) 16... fxe5 {How should White recapture the pawn?} 17. Nxe5 {Recapturing with a piece is best. This is because the [e5]-square that was once occupied by a pawn can now be occupied by a piece! This is especially good for White since the [e5]-square is an outpost that Black cannot attack with a pawn anymore.} Nd6 {Black decides to avoid the piece trades for now.} (17... Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 {+- is a classic example of a good knight vs. bad bishop. White will look to double rooks on the e-file and target Black's weak [e7]-pawn and exposed kingside.}) 18. Rc1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc1c6] Taking aim at the [c6]-pawn.} Bc8 19. Ncd3 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc1c6] Opening up the rook to hit [c6].} Bb7 {Black was forced to passivize their bishop due to the pawn weakness on [c6]. We'll talk more about pawn weaknesses in a future chapter.} 20. Bh2 $18 {White no longer has the space advantage, but if you compare the activity of the pieces, it is a night and day difference.} *

