{Black has a lot of their pieces stuck defending the [c6]-pawn, while their kingside is a bit exposed. Now White goes for the next phase of using a space advantage: Transferring pieces towards the opponent's kingside and building an attack!} 21. Qg4 {First the queen.} Kh8 22. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4g6,Ge5g6] Next the second knight. Capturing on [g6] is an idea now.} Qb6 23. Nexg6+ {White smells blood and calculates a winning attack.} hxg6 24. Nxg6+ Kh7 25. Bxd6 exd6 26. Qh5+ Bh6 27. Re7+ Kg8 28. Qxh6 {Black resigns, as checkmate is unstoppable. A well-played game by Wesley So! He secured his central space advantage by making it difficult for Black to apply pressure to the pawns Bb5, [h3], [Bf4], worked around the weaknesses that Black had in their position the [c6] and [e7]-pawns, and eventually transitioned into an attack towards Black's kingside that worked like a charm.} 1-0

