{We start in an opening position for this game. Space in the center of the board is equal with both sides having a pawn in the center. How can White increase their control of the center and gain a space advantage?} 6. c4 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gc4d5] Advancing the c-pawn gains more control over the [d5]-square. White now has two pawns along the fourth rank, compared to Black's one pawn on the fifth rank. It tends to be the case that whoever has more pawns on the fourth/fifth ranks has the space advantage. This also depends on whose pawns are more advanced and have any of the pawns pushed into the opponent's half of the board. In some positions, you can clarify this even more by saying that one player has more space on the queenside/center/kingside specifically.} c6 {[%csl Rc4,Rc6] In comparison, Black's c-pawn is not as far up the board and doesn't equalize the space difference between the two sides.} 7. Nc3 O-O {Black has played the opening passively and not fought for the control of the center as well as they could have. How can White gain an even bigger space advantage?} (7... e4 $1 {Black's best move is to push forward and look to turn the space advantage in their favor.} 8. Ne1 d5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. f3 $1 {Chipping away at the front of Black's pawn chain and neutralizing their space advantage:} exf3 11. Nxf3 {∞ . Space in the center has been equalized and an interesting middlegame would arise soon.}) 8. e4 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4,Re4,Re5] Advancing another pawn to the fourth rank. Now we have three pawns on the fourth rank near the center, compared to Black's one pawn on their fifth rank. Even if Black were to trade their [e5]-pawn for our [d4]-pawn, then we would still have a two vs. zero advantage in regards to pawns across the center. This space advantage means that it will be easier for White to maneuver their pieces behind the pawns compared to Black. Two glaring examples of this are Black's bishops. Neither one of them can move at all! The bishop on [e7] especially will have a hard time since Black's [d6] and [e5]-pawns are on the same color.} (8. Qc2 {± is another interesting option that prevents Black from playing ...[e4] and allows us to play [e4] ourselves soon.}) 8... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Phase one of gaining and using a space advantage is complete. We got the space advantage. Now we need to make sure that our opponent cannot break down our center too easily. Right now, they cannot play ...[d5] without losing material, and ...[c5] would allow us to play [d5] and cross into their half of the board. Instead of either of these moves, Black has just played ...[a6]. What is their idea behind this move, and how can we prevent this plan?} 9. a4 $1 {Black wanted to play ...[b5] to chip away at our [c4]-pawn and try to lessen our space advantage. By playing [a4], we stop this idea and put a fourth pawn on the fourth rank.} (9. Re1 $6 {A normal developing move wouldn't work against Black's idea of attacking our pawn center. After} b5 {⩲ , Black is able to put a second pawn on the fifth rank and chip away at our [c4]-pawn. White still has a good position, but we should shut this plan down before it can happen.}) 9... a5 {Black finally gets a second pawn on the fifth rank, but White has been able to secure the center well, and Black doesn't have an easy way to lessen our control of the center easily.} 10. h3 $16 {Taking away the [g4]-square from Black's knight so that [Be3] can be played without being bothered. White's space advantage is large and Black's pieces are cramped.} *

