{Over the past few moves, White had been developing more pieces to secure their space advantage and especially over-protecting the [e4]-pawn. Now that the center is secure, it is time to advance forward!} 15. f4 {We start advancing the pawns on the kingside to gain a bigger space advantage, further cramp Black's pieces, and eventually look to trade pawns and open up that half of the board to attack on.} Nfd7 16. g4 {More space! White is not concerned about any king safety issues since Black's pieces are so cramped that they cannot take advantage of it at all.} Bf8 {Because Black is lacking in space to such a drastic degree, they have a very difficult time maneuvering their pieces in a good way. The bishop on [e7] was in the way of the [e8]-rook, so it retreats and may go to [g7] soon.} 17. g5 Na6 18. h4 {The pawn avalanche continues.} Nb4 {Black's knight has moved forward from [c5] to [b4], but this one-move threat can be dealt with easily.} 19. Qe2 {Now Black's knight is shooting into thin air a bit.} Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3,Gb4d3] Black wants to put one of their knights on [d3]. Keep in mind that even if we are mostly focusing on the kingside part of the board and attacking, we should still be on the lookout for our opponent's plans and try to prevent them from happening. How can White prevent a knight from landing on [d3]?} 20. Rd1 {We take one move to stop Black's idea and then can go back to our kingside play.} Bd7 21. f5 {This pawn break may help to open up the f-file one day so that the [f1]-rook is more active.} Rad8 22. h5 $18 {Black's kingside pawn coverage is starting to creak a bit and will become compromised soon.} *

