{How should White play to break through on the kingside?} 24. hxg6 {First, White trades pawns to open the h-file.} hxg6 25. Rf4 $1 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gf4h4,Gd1h1,Ge2h2] This rook lift is a huge problem for Black. White is going to play [Rh4] and eventually get the queen or other rook to the h-file and go for checkmate on [h8]. Note how Black's lack of space makes it impossible for them to maneuver any pieces closer to the kingside to help defend against this build-up!} d5 {It's too late for this counterattack in the center.} 26. cxd5 Bd6 (26... cxd5 27. Rh4 $1 {White can ignore Black's attack on the center and simply focus on the h-file.} dxe4 28. Ndb5 Qg3 29. Qf2 Qxf2+ 30. Kxf2 {+- and there isn't much Black can do to stop [Rh1] and [Rh8]#.}) 27. Rh4 Bg3 28. Rh6 {The rook is safe and sound on [h6].} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4,Gc8g4] Black wants to play ...[Ng4] or ...[Bg4], but we can stop both of these ideas.} 29. Bf3 cxd5 30. Kg2 $1 {[%cal Gd1h1] Ignoring the center and simply looking to play [Rdh1] followed by checkmate on [h8].} *

