{White has a space advantage across the center and kingside. How can we look to make more progress using this advantage?} 1. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Advancing on the kingside with the goal of weakening Black's king makes a lot of sense. The idea is to push the h-pawn towards the [h6]-square.} Ra6 {Black tries to use the rook to defend the [e6]-pawn before playing ...[f6]. However, we can still continue with our plan.} (1... h6 $2 {This gives the bishop an escape square on [h7] but provides a hook on [h6], which gives us a pawn break possibility on [g5].} 2. h5 Bd3 3. g5 {, Black's kingside is getting opened quickly. After} hxg5 4. Nxg5 {+- , Black will have a hard time defending against the incoming attack. Moves like [Bf4], [Re3], [Qg4], and [Bf1] to trade off Black's bishop will be dangerous for them.}) ({Moving the bishop forward doesn't change anything about our kingside play:} 1... Bd3 2. h5 {± . We keep pushing and will provoke some weaknesses.}) 2. h5 Bd3 3. h6 {Provoking a weakness around Black's kingside.} g6 4. Bg5 $18 {Black's dark squres are very weak and White has good control of the position.} *

