{How should White recapture the pawn on [c4]?} 11. bxc4 {Recapturing with the pawn is best. We gain more control of the center and a bigger space advantage. Next, we want to play [e5] to further kick back Black's pieces.} (11. Bxc4 $6 {Recapturing this way gives us less control of the center.} Bb7 12. e5 Nd5 {± and Black is able to use the [d5]-square to facilitate a trade of pieces. White still has the advantage but not as much as in the main line.}) 11... e5 {Black can try to beat us to the punch and play ...[e5] themselves, but this will still result in a great position for us.} 12. dxe5 Ng4 13. e6 $1 {The pawn was doomed anyway so it is good to give it back in a favorable circumstance. Black has to recapture with their f-pawn, which blocks in their [e8]-rook and [c8]-bishop. This also gives us a free move to continue harassing Black's knights.} (13. Bf4 $5 {defends the pawn, but Black will be able to win it back soon anyway.} Qc7 {± and Black will capture [e5] next. White is still in good shape here, but the [e8]-rook and [c8]-bishop will not be blocked in.}) 13... fxe6 14. h3 {Driving back Black's pieces.} Nge5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Be3 $18 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5] White has a strong position. We still have a big space advantage and can play moves like [f4]+e5 later to advance in the center. Black's isolated pawn on [e6] cancels out our isolated pawn on [c4].} *

