{Black is offering a trade of knights. What should we do?} 12. Ne1 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gd1g4] Keeping a pair of pieces on the board. We avoid the trade and also threaten the [g4]-knight now. The knights are stepping on each other's toes and must back up to stay safe.} (12. Nxe5 $6 {Trading knights allows Black to relieve some of the cramps on their position.} Nxe5 {⩲ and now there's one less pair of pieces on the board for Black to worry about.}) (12. Nd2 {± is another option for avoiding the trade of knights, but now the bishop on [d2] is blocked in.}) 12... Nf6 13. f4 {Black's knights continue to get driven backwards.} Ng6 14. g4 $18 {White has a large space advantage across the board and the bishop pair on top of that. Even though our king is slightly exposed when we push the pawns, Black doesn't have a way to take advantage of this.} *

