[Black "Pawn Weakness − Definition"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654361929864"]

{A pawn weakness is defined as a pawn that cannot easily be defended by a friendly pawn. This includes things such as isolated pawns, doubled pawns, and backward pawns. It's important to note that the ability to attack a weak pawn defines whether it is actually weak; in other words, a pawn is only considered weak if it can be attacked. Conversely, if a pawn cannot be easily attacked, it may not be a weakness at all. On the other hand, if a pawn can be attacked by multiple pieces, then it will be a problem for its player. Let's see some examples of weak pawns in the next few positions.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pawn Weakness"]
[Black "Pawn Weakness − Example #1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1rr3k1/5pp1/p3pnp1/3p4/3P1qP1/PNP4P/Q4P2/2R2RK1 b - - 0 23"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654361954441"]

{Here, White has a number of pawn weaknesses. The pawn on [a3] is 'isolated', which means that there is no friendly pawn on the file next to it. The pawn on [c3] is 'backwards', which means that the pawn is behind a pawn on an adjacent file but cannot be defended easily by a friendly pawn. The pawns on [h3] and [f2] are somewhat backwards too since White's g-pawn has moved forward from the [g2]-square. It's important to consider which of all these pawn weaknesses is actually the easiest for us to attack with multiple pieces. Clearly, the [c3]-pawn is the primary weakness. It is on a half-open file which means our rooks can target it. Also, our knight can jump into [e4] and harass it as well. On the other hand, the [a3] and [h3]-pawns are difficult to attack with multiple pieces and the [f2]-pawn can be defended multiple times easily. For this reason, Black's plan should revolve around targeting the [c3]-pawn and aiming to win it. You can see how the game continued by clicking here.} 23... Z0 *

