[Black "Pawn Weakness − How to Gain This Advantage"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654361966731"]

{Creating pawn weaknesses in your opponent's position is a crucial skill, and a few effective ways to gain this advantage are: Trade pieces in a way that creates a weak pawn structure. Use pawn breaks to provoke weaknesses. Attack pawns with pieces in order to provoke weaknesses.} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pawn Weakness"]
[Black "Pawn Weakness − Blueprint to Convert"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2133654361974924"]

{Once we've created a pawn weakness for our opponent, then there's one main plan to work towards: capturing the weak pawn and being ahead in material! However, there are a few guiding principles to be aware of when you are going after an opponent's weak pawn. The first principle when playing against an opponent's pawn weakness is to control the square in front of the pawn or blockade the pawn. This is important because if we attack the pawn with multiple pieces but it advances, we may need to reposition our pieces to target the pawn on a different square. Additionally, in some cases, the opponent will want to advance their pawn in order to trade it off. If the opponent can trade off their weak pawn, then this advantage will disappear for us. Another factor to consider is that pawn weaknesses are magnified as pieces are traded off the board. This is because if a position is very complex and messy, or if the opponent creates some dynamic counterplay, then they may be able to distract us from focusing on the weak pawn. On the other hand, if there are less pieces on the board and the game is closer to the endgame, there tends to be less dynamism in the position to distract us from attacking and winning the pawn. Finally, just because the opponent has one weak pawn doesn't mean we are guaranteed to win it. A good opponent will defend the weak pawn and make us work really hard to win it if it is even possible. In these cases, it can be good to work towards gaining a second advantage elsewhere on the board. We might be able to also gain the bishop pair, create a second weak pawn, or weaken the opponent's king. The more problems our opponent has, the better for us. They might be able to plug one leak in a dam, but trying to plug/defend multiple leaks/problems will leave them stretched thin and vulnerable. The blueprint looks like this: ➝ Create a weak pawn for the opponent ➝ Control the square in front of the pawn or blockade the pawn so it cannot advance easily ➝ Maneuver pieces towards attacking the pawn ➝ Trade pieces to lower the dynamism of the position ➝ Tie down the opponent's pieces that are defending the pawn ➝ Win the pawn or create a second weakness/advantage in a different part of the board if you cannot win the pawn immediately. Let's move on to a few examples where we will see this blueprint in action.} 1. Z0 *

