[PlyCount "3"]
[GameId "2133654361983117"]

{White has just captured a piece on [c4]. How should Black recapture in order to create play against a weak pawn in White's position?} 18... bxc4 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb8b2] By recapturing with the b-pawn we are able to open up the half-open file towards White's [b2]-pawn. This pawn is a long-term weakness since it is backwards and cannot be defended by a friendly pawn easily. If the pawn ever moves forward then we can capture it with our [c4]-pawn and that pawn trade will result in White being left with weak pawns on [a3] and [c3] aftewards.} (18... dxc4 $6 {Recapturing with the d-pawn is not as good since it doesn't create a new weakness for the opponent. After} 19. Bxg6 hxg6 {⩱ , Black still has some advantage but not as much as in the game.}) 19. Bxg6 hxg6 $17 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b6,Gc8b8,Gb8b7,Gd6b8] Black has doubled pawns, but these are not weak since the front pawn is well supported by the [f7]-pawn. The game plan for Black is to double the rooks on the b-file along with the queen helping out. That would put a ton of pressure on White's [b2]-pawn and Black would most likely win it at some point.} (19... fxg6 {∞ , recapturing with the f-pawn gives us a weakness on [e6] for no good reason.}) *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pawn Weakness"]
[Black "Allen Li − Felix Xie, Trusts Open 2023 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1r3k1/5pp1/p2qpnp1/3p4/1PpP2P1/P1P4P/3N1P2/1QR2RK1 b - b3 0 20"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2133654361991310"]

{White has just played [b2]-[b4]. How can we punish this move?} 20... cxb3 {We can capture en passant and create new weaknesses.} 21. Qxb3 {[%csl Rc3] Now White is left with an isolated [a3]-pawn, but especially their backward [c3]-pawn is the real weakness here. This is because we can use rooks to attack the [c3]-pawn while the [a3]-pawn is harder to attack due to our own pawn being on [a6] and blocking off the file for any rooks to use.} Rab8 22. Qa2 Qf4 $19 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3,Rg1,Rh3] Black improves their pieces with each move. Aside from the weak queenside pawns, White's king is exposed as well. This combination of multiple weak spots in White's position is incredibly difficult to deal with since their pieces are getting pulled in multiple directions trying to defend everything at once.} *

[Event "Seal the Deal: How to Gain and Convert Middlegame Advantages"]
