{Black has just played 18...f5, attacking White's pawn center. This was a mistake though that allowed Carlsen to create a weak pawn in Black's position. How can White create this long-term weakness?} 19. exd5 $1 {By trading pawns on [d5] we will be leaving Black with an isolated d-pawn.} cxd5 {This [d5]-pawn cannot be defended by any of Black's friendly pawns and will need pieces to defend it for the rest of the game. It is true that White also ends up with an isolated d-pawn of our own but it is more difficult for Black to attack it multiple times. How can we continue to target Black's [d5]-pawn with more pieces?} 20. Ba2 {The bishop switches to a different diagonal where there is a weakness to target. Black's [d5]-pawn is weaker than White's [d4]-pawn partly because our bishop can attack their pawn while their bishop cannot cannot attack our pawn.} Qd6 {Already two of Black's pieces are stuck passively, defending the [d5]-pawn.} 21. Rfe1 {The rook gets onto the open e-file and will help in the attack on the [d5]-pawn soon.} a6 {So far we have the bishop and [c3]-knight targeting Black's [d5]-pawn. How can we maneuver the other knight and rook to help in the attack on [d5]?} 22. Nc1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc1d3,Gd3b4,Ge1e5] Carlsen retreats the knight but is going to maneuver it towards the [b4]-square. The rook can also now move to [e5] to help attack the weak pawn.} Rfe8 23. Re5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge5d5] Attacker number three.} Nc7 24. Nd3 Nge6 25. Nb4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb4d5] Attacker number four. Black has run out of ways to defend the [d5]-pawn and it will be captured next.} Kg7 26. Nbxd5 {Now that Carlsen is ahead a pawn, the process of converting the material advantage takes place. The first goal is to trade pieces and simplify the position.} Nxd5 27. Bxd5 Bxd5 28. Rxd5 $18 {Two pairs of pieces have left the board. The rest of the conversion process can be examined in the next informational.} *

