{How can Black play to open up some lines for their pieces to work towards targeting the backward [d4]-pawn in the near future?} 16... b6 $1 {This pawn break will either open the [a7]-[d4] diagonal towards the weak pawn or result in White having a weak pawn on [c5].} 17. cxb6 {This pawn trade is White's best move in an otherwise rough position.} (17. Be3 $2 {If White doesn't trade pawns on [b6], then we will capture on [c5].} bxc5 18. dxc5 e5 {-+ , White's [c5]-pawn is still a bit weak since it isn't easy to defend with their b-pawn. Playing [b4] anytime soon would allow us to get rid of the b-pawn by playing ...[axb4]. Also, we now have a big space advantage in the center with threats of ...[d4] and ideas to play ...[e4] at opportune times.}) 17... Qxb6 $17 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb6d4] Now that the [c5]-pawn is gone, Black can target the [d4]-pawn along the diagonal with the queen. A rook can also go to the open c-file and aim at White's queen. The pawn is easier for us to attack now and that makes it more of a liability for White to deal with.} *

