{White is defending the [d4]-pawn for now, but Black wants to put more pressure on it soon. How can Black maneuver a new piece to attack the [d4]-pawn soon?} 19... Ne8 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7f6] This clears out the [f6]-square so that the bishop can go there to target [d4]. Also, there might be ideas of ...[Nc7]-[b5] or ...[Nd6]-[f5] to target the pawn too.} (19... Nd7 {∓ also gets the knight off the [f6]-square, but the knight isn't able to maneuver from the [d7]-square easily.}) 20. Rab1 Bf6 $17 {[%csl Rc2,Rd4][%cal Gc6b4,Ge8d6,Gd6f5] Black has a pleasant advantage due to the ability to attack White's isolated [d4]-pawn. After White defends the pawn, then we can play ...[Nb4] to trade off one of the pawn defenders. Later the maneuver ...[Nd6]-[f5] will help to attack the pawn with another piece.} *

