{How can White play to create a pawn weakness?} 20. Bxd5 {Trading the bishop for the knight on [d5] will create an isolated d-pawn for Black.} exd5 {[%csl Rd5]} 21. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Rd5] Aiming one of the rooks towards the pawn and defending our knight is good. White shouldn't be in a rush to capture the d-pawn just yet if it allows Black to get a lot of counterplay. The [d5]-pawn is a long-term weakness and that isn't going to change anytime soon. We can look to win the pawn at a more ideal moment later on.} (21. Rfd1 {± , using this rook to go to [d1] is also good.}) (21. Qxd5 $6 {Rushing to capture the d-pawn is risky due to the activity that Black gains.} Rd8 {, this skewer along the d-file is tricky for White to deal with. After} 22. Qa8 {, White has to move to [a8] so that if Black captures our knight then we can capture their knight.} Qf6 {, Black attacks our knight and [b2]-pawn behind it if it moves.} 23. e3 Nc6 {and now there's a discovered attack on our queen.} 24. Qxa6 Nxd4 {, another discovered attack on our queen,} 25. Qxf6 Ne2+ 26. Kg2 gxf6 {∞ . Stockfish says this position is equal, but I would rather play Black with the material advantage.}) *

