{Later in the game, White has maneuvered their pieces to better squares and now has the chance to cash in and win material. How can we do that?} 26. Rxc5 $1 {Trading rooks allows us to either win the [d5]-pawn or maneuver our queen to win the [a5]-pawn.} Nxc5 {Black attacks our queen and [a4]-pawn.} (26... Qxc5 {, recapturing with the queen allows Black to defend the [b5]-square but ends up losing the [d5]-pawn instead.} 27. Nb3 {, the queen and [d5]-pawn are both hit.} Qc6 28. Qxd5 Qxa4 29. Nc5 {and Black loses a piece due to the pin along the d-file:} Qb5 30. Nxd7 Qxd5 31. Rxd5 {+- .}) 27. Qb5 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rd8,Re7][%cal Gb5a5,Gd4c6] Defending the [a4]-pawn and attacking [a5] at the same time. In addition, White is threatening the fork with [Nc6]. Black cannot defend everything at the same time.} Rd7 28. Qxa5 $18 {White wins a pawn and went on to convert their material advantage later.} 1-0

