{White has a weak backward pawn on [d4]. How can we apply more pressure to the pawn?} 1... Be4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge4f3] We're not targeting the pawn directly but instead, we're attacking one of the defenders of the pawn.} 2. a3 {White counterattacks our bishop.} (2. Nxe4 $2 {Capturing the bishop would lose material for White. Following} dxe4 3. Ng5 Qxd4 {-+ , Black wins a pawn and has a big advantage. The [e5]-pawn is now undefended too.}) 2... Bxd2+ {We make the trade.} 3. Nxd2 {[%csl Rh5] White is trying to get counterplay based on opening up an attack on our [h5]-pawn.} (3. Qxd2 $2 {Recapturing with the queen allows us to win [d4] without a fight. After} Bxf3 4. Bxf3 Qxd4 {, we will capture the [e5]-pawn next:} 5. Qxd4 Nxd4 {-+ . White cannot capture [h5] since a fork on [c2] is threatened. After they deal with the fork, then we can play ...[g6] to defend our h-pawn and secure our material advantage.}) 3... Bg6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Gc6d4,Gb6b2] Retreating the bishop is fine since White has trouble defending both [d4] and [b2].} 4. Nb3 {The only way to defend both pawns.} a5 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Ga5a4] Now our a-pawn barrels down the board to kick the knight away. White is under constant pressure since it is not easy for them to keep defending the weaknesses on [d4] and [b2].} *

