{Black has the opportunity to create a favorable imbalance in the position and weaken White's pawn structure. How can we do that?} 10... Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gg4e3] Attacking the bishop, which is stuck defending the [d4]-knight.} 11. Nc2 {Moving the knight backwards avoids doubled e-pawns but allows Black to create a different pawn weakness.} (11. Nxc6 $2 {This capture would be okay if Black had to recapture immediately. However, that isn't forced.} Nxe3 $1 {An important in-between move that creates a weak pawn structure for White. Black is attacking White's queen so White needs to react.} 12. fxe3 bxc6 {-+ , Black is much better due to the strong bishop and White's double isolated e-pawns being long-term weaknesses.}) (11. Qd2 $2 {allows Black to create a pawn weakness on the e-file.} Nxe3 12. fxe3 O-O {∓ and White has long-term problems due to the double isolated e-pawns. Black's bishop is also very strong in the upcoming middlegame.}) 11... Bxc3 $1 {With this trade, White will end up with double isolated c-pawns, which will be a long-term problem for them.} (11... Nxe3 $5 12. Nxe3 {⩱ , Black is also slightly better here whether they trade on [c3] and weaken White's pawn structure or not.}) 12. bxc3 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4]} Rc8 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc6a5,Gd7e6,Gg4e5] We can target their pawns with additional moves like ...[Na5], ...[Nge5] and ...[Qe6]. White will struggle to keep the pawns safe in the long run and will most likely lose material on the queenside.} *

