{Black has an isolated d-pawn. This is a long-term weakness due to no friendly pawn being able to defend it. This means that the d-pawn will need constant protection from pieces rooks or queen. These high-value pieces would really rather be doing anything else than defending a 1-point pawn, but losing the pawn is not really a good alternative. How can White play from here to capitalize on this weakness?} 17. Rad1 {Immediately targeting the pawn. This rook also controls the [d4]-square so that we don't need to worry about Black pushing their pawn forward and trading it off.} Rad8 {Defending the pawn and hinting at potentially pushing the pawn to [d4] to trade it off.} 18. Rd4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf1d1] Blockading the pawn is a great idea since it prevents the pawn from advancing and trading itself off while also preparing to double the rooks on the d-file.} Rfe8 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge5d4,Ge8e2] Setting up a threat of ...[Qxd4] due to the pin along the e-file.} 19. Rfd1 {Defending the rook on [d4] while also continuing to apply pressure to the pawn.} Rd6 {Black rushes to double their own rooks to defend [d5].} 20. Qb5 {[%csl Rd5,Rb7] Attacking the [d5]-pawn a third time but also targeting the [b7]-pawn. Black cannot defend both weaknesses at the same time.} Rh6 {Trying to create counterplay on the kingside, but this is only a one-move threat.} 21. h3 {We defend against Black's threat and will win the [b7] or [d5]-pawn next move.} Rf8 22. Qxb7 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Ra7] Black is down a pawn and will lose a second pawn soon due to the pressure on [d5] and [a7].} *

