{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 16... h6 $1 {Rather than trading knight for bishop, we can instead kick the bishop back to [e3] where we'll create a pawn weakness for our opponent.} (16... Nxg5 {∓ was played in the game. This does gain the bishop pair advantage, but it would have actually been even better to gain a pawn structure advantage instead.}) (16... f6 $5 {is another way to force the bishop back to [e3], but it feels unnecessary to open our king and pin our [e6]-knight:} 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. fxe3 {∓ .}) 17. Be3 ({White has to go back to e3 to avoid losing material. After} 17. Bh4 $2 g5 {-+ , the bishop is trapped and we win a piece.}) 17... Bxe3 $19 {[%csl Re3,Re4] After White recaptures, they'll be stuck with double isolated e-pawns. This takes away one of their potential pawn breaks f4 and leaves them with weak pawns and little counterplay.} *

