{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 13... Qe4 $1 {[%csl Rd5,Rd4] Putting pressure on both d-pawns at the same time. White has a hard time defending both of them in a good way.} 14. Bc4 $2 {White tries to defend the [d5]-pawn but will run into trouble from a different angle.} (14. h3 {was played in the game.} Qxd5 {⩱ and Black is up a clear pawn while White still has an isolated d-pawn left over.}) 14... Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rh4][%cal Gg4f3,Ge4h4,Ge4d4] By pinning and attacking the knight not only are we looking to eliminate a defender of the [d4]-pawn but the defender of the [h4]-bishop too!} 15. Re1 {White tries to distract us by attacking our queen.} Bxf3 $1 {We can ignore White's attack and continue with our idea since this attacks White's queen as well.} 16. Rxe4 {White has to capture our queen to avoid losing material immediately.} Bxd1 17. Rxd1 {White has seemingly kept everything defended, but the final wrinkle to the position highlights the bad placement of the [h4]-bishop and [e4]-rook.} g5 {[%csl Re4,Rh4][%cal Gg5h4,Gf7f5,Gf5f4] This bishop will be trapped by the kingside pawns very soon.} (17... f5 $5 {This move order also wins a piece but does allow a bit more counterplay from White:} 18. Re6 g5 19. Bxg5 hxg5 20. Rg6+ Kh8 21. Rxg5 Nd7 {-+ . Black is ahead material with a good advantage, but White did at least get two pawns for the bishop.}) 18. Bg3 f5 19. Re6 f4 $19 {White loses the bishop and Black has a big advantage.} 0-1

