{In regards to summarizing the principles and blueprints for converting advantages, I have listed them out in a straightforward 'if... then...' format. This streamlined list brings together everything shown throughout the course in one convenient place. Hope you find it helpful! 1. IF you have a long-term/static/strategic advantage, THEN you should: Usually be patient and not rush things. Prioritize preventing the opponent's counterplay by using prophylaxis. Work to restrict your opponent's pieces so they are hard to activate. Trade pieces in favorable ways get rid of the opponent's good pieces. Avoid unfavorable trades don't trade off your good pieces without good reason. Play around a good vs. bad minor piece imbalance. Try to accumulate more advantages as the game progresses. Aim to create multiple weaknesses or problems for the opponent if possible. 2. IF you have a king safety advantage, THEN you should: Look for pawn trades and pawn breaks towards the opponent's king in order to open more lines and files for your bishops and rooks. Consider sacrifices to blast open the opponent's king. Maneuver your pieces towards the opponent's king. Try to provoke weaknesses around your opponent's king. Work towards gaining other advantages along the way. Aim to attack and ultimately checkmate your opponent's king. 3. IF you have a material advantage, THEN you should: Trade pieces especially queens in order to simplify the position and get closer to the endgame. Try to limit the dynamism in the position so that you can get to the endgame phase with your material advantage intact. Use your extra material especially if you're ahead a piece to attack your opponent's king with a firepower superiority. 4. IF you have a bishop pair advantage, THEN you should: Look for ways to trade pawns in order to open the position. Push for pawn breaks that will help to open the position. Don't lock or close the position. Play around the color of the bishop that you have that the opponent doesn't. 5. IF you have a space advantage, THEN you should: Push your pawns further forward to cramp the opponent's position even more. Avoid trading pieces unless it is beneficial for you. Secure your center and overprotect the pawns that are giving you the space advantage. Use your advantage in piece mobility to maneuver towards the opponent's king and start an attack. Look for pawn breaks towards the opponent's king to help facilitate an attack. 6. IF you have a pawn weakness advantage, THEN you should: Control the square in front of the weak pawn so that it cannot advance easily. Trade pieces so that there is less dynamism in the position to distract you from attacking the weak pawn. Attack the weak pawn with multiple pieces in order to win it or tie your opponent's pieces down to passively protect the pawn. Work to create additional weaknesses in the opponent's position if you cannot win the first weakness easily.} 1. Z0 *

