{In this example, we will see a situation where we begin with a space advantage and then transform this advantage into a different one. First of all, White has more space in the center due to the [c4] and [d5]-pawns vs. Black's [e5]-pawn. Black has just pushed their pawn from [e7] to [e5], attacking our knight. Here we have a good way to respond to this.} 17. dxe6 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge7e5,Ge5d4] Capturing en passant allows us to weaken Black's pawn structure. Black's [d6]-pawn will be a target on the half-open d-file no matter how they recapture. This does cost us some of our space advantage, but the long-term weakness will be worth it.} (17. Nc2 $2 Rec8 {∞ , moving the knight maintains the space advantage but allows Black to stay solid since they have no real weaknesses. It's better for us to give up some of our space advantage in order to create a long-term weakness that we can attack.}) 17... Nxe6 {Black recaptures with the knight to facilitate a piece trade.} ({Black could also recapture with the f-pawn so that the d6-pawn doesn't become isolated:} 17... fxe6 {. However, the two pawns on [d6] and [e6] are still a bit weak in a 'hanging pawns structure'. I like to think of these two pawns as one big, wide isolated pawn since there is no c-pawn or f-pawn to support either of the two pawns. With this in mind, the pawns are still a bit weak and can become targets.} 18. Qc2 {, we move the queen to control the [e4]-square so that we can continue with [Ndb5] and target the [d6]-pawn.} Rf8 {, opening the [e8]-square for the knight to help defend the weakness on [d6].} 19. Ndb5 {, pressuring the [d6]-pawn. After} Ne8 20. Be3 {+- , we can play [Ne4] or [b4] next in order to continue moving forward and putting more pressure on Black.}) 18. Nxe6 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d6] Trading off our knight, which was blocking the d-file. Now we're opening our queen and rook towards the [d6]-pawn.} Rxe6 19. Rxe6 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd7e6,Gg5e3,Gc3b5]} (19. Rxe6 {Trading more pieces so that the pawn weakness is magnified. After} Bxe6 {, we cannot capture the [d6]-pawn yet since our [b2]-pawn would hang. However, the weak pawn is going to stay on the board in the long term. We can play [Be3] to attack the queen and [Nb5] to target the [d6]-pawn; Black will be burdened with the weak pawn for the rest of the game.}) *

