{This position features a nice sequence of moves that allows White to transform a space advantage into a good vs. bad piece advantage. At the start, White has a space advantage with the [c4]+d4-pawns vs. Black's [c5]-pawn. White can use this extra space to create trouble for Black quickly.} 17. d5 $1 {Pushing forward allows us to increase our space advantage or transform it into a good vs. bad piece imbalance.} (17. Na4 {⩲ was played in the game, but an opportunity was missed.}) 17... exd5 (17... Ne5 {, moving the knight still leaves Black with a passive position and a space disadvantage. After} 18. Nf4 {+- , Black's bishops are terrible and White is in great shape with a big advantage.}) 18. Nf4 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Re7][%cal Gf4d5,Gc3d5] White is going to capture on [d5] and end up with a knight on a strong outpost rather than having the bishop end up on [d5]. Because [Nxd5] is a fork, Black cannot avoid this outcome. You could call this a 'delayed recapture' since Black cannot save the pawn without losing more material.} (18. Nxd5 $5 {Recapturing with the knight is okay, but we will end up with a bishop on [d5] instead of a knight. Following} Nxd5 19. Bxd5 {+- , White is still much better due to the piece activity but wouldn't you rather have a knight on [d5] instead?!}) (18. cxd5 $2 {Recapturing with the pawn does give us some space advantage, but the [d5]-pawn is blocking things up rather than helping.} Ne5 19. Ne4 {⩲ and White is still for choice, but a piece on [d5] would be better.}) 18... Ba7 {Retreating the bishop to keep it safe.} (18... dxc4 $4 {Black cannot be this greedy.} 19. Ncd5 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 {+- and Black loses a piece due to the fork.}) 19. Ncxd5 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 {[%csl Re8,Ra7] White's strong knight dominates the board. Also, look at Black's terrible bishops!} Qe6 21. Qa1 $18 {[%csl Rd6] Targeting the [g7]-pawn. White has a huge advantage due to their much more active pieces. Black also has a long-term weak backward pawn on [d6] that can be targeted later.} *

