{Yu Yangyi found a good way to play that transforms the bishop pair advantage into a material advantage.} 18. Be3 $1 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Ge3a7] Hitting the queen but mainly targeting the [a7]-pawn further back in the diagonal.} Qxb2 {Black grabs a pawn in response.} (18... Qd6 {counterattacks the [c6]-bishop and is better than capturing the [b2]-pawn, but White can still keep the advantage.} 19. Rc1 {, defending the bishop and continuing to threaten the [a7]-pawn. (19.Bxa7?? It's not safe to grab the pawn in this situation. After 19...Qxc6 20.Bxb8 Bb7 -+ , Black threatens both checkmate and our bishop, which is bad news for us. )} Qc7 20. Qe2 {± and White maintains a strong position with the active pieces and bishop pair.}) 19. Bxa7 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Ga7b8] Now the rook on [b8] is trapped and White will win the exchange.} Bb7 {Black reacts in a way that will leave them with a strong light-squared bishop in return for being down the exchange.} 20. Bxb8 $18 {White will come out ahead an exchange.} (20. Bxb7 $2 {is too passive. White should grab the rook and continue with that advantage.} Rxb7 21. Bc5 Rd8 {∞ and White has no advantage here. The isolated a- and d-pawns are weak in the long term.}) *

