{What is the best way to play to transform our current long-term advantage into a new long-term advantage?} 29. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rb5][%cal Gc1a3,Gc3b5] Attacking the rook but also breaking the pin on the third rank. This means that the knight is attacking the [b5]-pawn now too. We're guaranteed to win material, but it will cost us our space advantage in the process.} Rxc3 $5 {Black decides to sacrifice the exchange rather than lose the [b5]-pawn.} ({After} 29... Ra6 30. Nxb5 {+- , White is up a clean pawn with a pleasant advantage. The plan is to push the passed b-pawn down the board later.}) 30. Nxc3 Nxd4 {Black has one pawn for the exchange and might start to use their passed c- and d-pawns in the near future. How to play as White?} 31. Rd1 $1 {It's very important to attack the knight and force it to trade for the bishop on [c2]. The knight cannot avoid the trade, as retreating would cost Black the [d5]-pawn.} Nxc2 {We're happy to have Black make more piece exchanges since we're ahead material.} 32. Qxc2 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Gd4] White is ahead the exchange for one pawn. As long as we prevent Black from playing ...[d4] safely, the bishop on [b7] will be bad, hemmed in by all the light-squared pawns. Carlsen went on to control the [d4]-square, blockade the d-pawn, and later won with his extra material.} 1-0

