{What is the best way to play to transform our current long-term advantage into a new long-term advantage?} 26... e4 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Ge4d3] We're able to use our big space advantage and push our pawns forward in the center with tempo on White's bishop. This will eventually lead to the ability to attack White's weak king.} (26... b4 $6 {was played in the game. Black did go for ...[e4] a move later, but it was more precise to push forward in the center immediately.} 27. a5 e4 28. fxe4 dxe4 29. Bc4 {∞ .}) 27. fxe4 dxe4 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Rg1][%cal Gg6f4,Ge8e5,Gg8h8,Gc8g8] White cannot capture the pawn due to the pressure on their [a1]-rook. After the bishop retreats, we can continue moving our pieces forward with ...[Nf4], ...[Re5], ...[Kh8] and ...[Rg8]. Our space advantage very quickly transforms into an attack on White's kingside.} *

