{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 10... cxd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e3] Capturing on [d4] first is the most precise. We gain time by attacking White's dark-squared bishop.} (10... dxe5 $6 {Capturing on [e5] first is possible but not as strong.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {⩱ , the difference here is that White's [c4]-pawn is more difficult to attack since we cannot use a rook or queen on the c-file to hit it.}) 11. cxd4 ({After} 11. exf6 $2 dxe3 12. fxg7 Rg8 {-+ , White is still left with a bunch of weak pawns on the queenside and Black ends up with a bigger advantage.}) 11... dxe5 {Now we trade on [e5].} 12. dxe5 Nd7 $17 {[%csl Rc4] White has weak isolated pawns on [c4] and [a3]. The [c4]-pawn will especially be a target for us to attack in the long term.} *

