{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 16. Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Re7][%cal Gd5e7,Gb2e5] Ignoring the attack on our queen and instead attacking Black's queen. We also open up our bishop on [b2] to help attack the [e5]-bishop. This doesn't win material but does gain us several other strategic advantages.} cxd5 ({The only move that doesn't lose material for Black.} 16... Bxd4 $4 17. Nxe7+ Kh8 18. Bxd4 {+- and White is now ahead a piece.}) ({And after} 16... Nxd5 $4 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. Bxe5 Nf6 19. Bd6 {+- , White is ahead a pawn in this variation and has the bishop pair as well.}) 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. Bxe5 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6][%cal Gf6e4,Gd5e4,Ge5f6] Black can equalize the material by capturing on [e4], but we will still continue to have the bishop pair advantage. Also, depending on how Black captures [e4], they may be left with an isolated d-pawn or give us the opportunity to capture on [f6] to weaken their kingside pawn structure.} *

