{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 11. d4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6] Expanding in the center ASAP is important to do. If Black is given a free move, then they could play ...[Nc6] to gain more control over the [d4]-square. Here, we get to gain a space advantage, while also trading off our backward [d3]-pawn, which could have become a weakness.} cxd4 12. Nxd4 {We recapture this way to keep the queens alive.} (12. Qxd4 $6 {We shouldn't be in a rush to trade queens when we have a space advantage.} Qxd4 13. Nxd4 Rd8 {∞ and Black is doing fine here with the queens off the board.}) 12... Qc8 {[%cal Gf8d8] Black's queen sidesteps the d-file, potentially paving the way for ...[Rd8] next.} 13. e5 $16 {[%csl Rg7,Rg8][%cal Gf6d7,Gd1g4] We can press forward in the center and attack Black's knight. Black cannot trade bishops on [g2] due to our in-between move [exf6]. Playing ...[Nd5] is also bad since it will result in an isolated pawn for Black after the pieces are traded. Finally, after ...[Nfd7] we can play [Qg4] and work towards an attack against Black's kingside using our space advantage and better piece mobility.} *

