{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 8. g4 $1 {Black's bishop on [f5] runs low on squares. We can gain the bishop pair advantage and create a pawn weakness as well.} Bg6 (8... Be4 {allows us to pick up the bishop pair immediately.} 9. Nxe4 dxe4 {, recapturing with the knight runs into [Bb5] problems.} 10. Qe2 {+- and Black will also lose the [e4]-pawn pretty soon.}) (8... Nxe5 $4 {runs into a huge attack.} 9. dxe5 Nxg4 {, Black is ahead one pawn, but there is no way to block the [a4]-[e8] diagonal anymore.} 10. Qa4+ Ke7 {, blocking with the queen ran into a [Bb5] pin.} 11. Qb4+ Kd7 12. Qxb7+ Qc7 13. Bb5+ Kd8 14. Qxa8+ {+- .}) 9. h4 $1 {It's important to not rush to capture the bishop immediately. We want to provoke a weakness first by threatening [h5], trapping the bishop.} (9. Nxg6 $2 {Trading on [g6] immediately does gain the bishop pair but in a worse way compared to the main line.} hxg6 {∞ , Black is able to recapture with their h-pawn, which means they have no real pawn weakness and they also open the rook on the h-file at the same time.}) 9... h6 {Freeing up a square for the bishop to retreat, but this is exactly what we wanted to provoke.} (9... Qc7 {, attacking the knight doesn't fix the problems.} 10. Nxd7 $1 {Trading on [d7] gets rid of Black's threat and leaves the bishop on [g6] to be harassed next. After} Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bg2 {+- , we have the bishop pair and better pawn structure.}) 10. Nxg6 $18 {[%csl Re6,Rg6][%cal Gf1d3,Gd1e2,Gf7g6] Now we capture on [g6] since the f-pawn has to recapture. This severely weakens Black's pawn structure since the [e6]-pawn will be backward and the [g6]-pawn will be a target. We can continue with [Bd3], and [Qe2] and put a lot of pressure on Black's weaknesses.} *

