{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 12. Bxc6 $1 {Trading on [c6] creates a backward [c6]-pawn for the opponent.} (12. Nxc6 $6 {Trading this way is not as good since our knight on [e5] was actually one of our strongest pieces.} bxc6 13. Ba6 Rce8 14. Nb3 Nh5 $1 {This move muddies the waters since Black is going to be able to gain the bishop pair themselves. It isn't possible for Black to play this move in the main line since [Nd7] would be a problematic fork.} 15. Be5 f6 {, our bishop is forced back to [g3] and Black can play ...[Nxg3] and ...[e5] to open the position.}) 12... bxc6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gc6c5] Black now threatens ...[Qxb2] and ...[c5].} 13. Nb3 {Preventing both of Black's ideas. We gain more control of the [c5]-square and will play [Rac1] next to put more pressure on the c-pawn.} c5 $6 {It seems reasonable to make this push and trade off the weak pawn, but White has a good answer in mind.} (13... h6 {, any other move allows White to develop a rook to the c-file and put pressure on the c-pawn. After} 14. Rac1 {± , Black faces an uphill battle due to their weak queenside pawns.}) 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5,Rf8][%cal Gg5f6,Ge5d7] Black cannot deal with the threat of [Bxf6] followed by [Nd7], forking the queen, rook and [c5]-bishop. Black will lose material now and White has a big advantage.} *

