{How can we play to gain the best version of a long-term advantage?} 10. dxc5 $1 {It's best to capture this way first in order to limit Black's options. Their [d5]-pawn is pinned along the diagonal so there is no other option for Black than to recapture on [c5].} (10. cxd5 $6 {Capturing this way does win a pawn but gives Black much more counterplay:} cxd4 $1 11. dxe6 Bxg2 12. exf7+ Rxf7 13. Kxg2 Qd5+ 14. Nf3 Nc6 {∞ . We're ahead a pawn, but Black's pieces are very active, our king is slightly weak, and the [d4]-pawn is not easy to attack quickly.}) 10... bxc5 11. cxd5 {Now we trade on [d5] since Black doesn't have the option of ...[cxd4] anymore.} exd5 {Black has a 'hanging pawns' structure. A good way of playing against this pawn structure is to separate the pawn duo with a pawn break of our own. If we can get the pawns to both be on the same color or isolate one of the two pawns, then we will create weaknesses.} (11... Bxd5 {was played in the game but results in Black having a weak isolated c-pawn with no compensation.} 12. e4 {⩲ , White has a good position due to Black's pawn weakness on [c5].}) 12. b4 $1 {This pawn break results in Black having an isolated d-pawn.} cxb4 (12... c4 $4 {Black cannot safely advance their c-pawn to avoid an isolated pawn.} 13. Nxc4 {+- and we win a pawn due to the pin along the diagonal.}) 13. axb4 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rd5][%cal Gc1b2,Gd2b3] Black is left with two weak isolated pawns on [a7] and [d5]. We do have an isolated b-pawn of our own, but the fact that both of Black's pawns are on half-open files and can easily be attacked is an advantage for us.} *

