{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 11. b3 $18 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc5c4,Gd3c4,Gb3c4] We can cement the [c5]-pawn in place and not allow Black to play ...[c4]. If they cannot play this move easily, then they will be stuck with doubled c-pawns and have a harder time opening the position for their bishop pair. Now that ...[c4] cannot be played, we can work towards playing [e5] soon in order to break Black's [d6]-[c5] pawn chain and weaken Black's [c5]-pawn. Later this pawn can be targeted with [Ne4]/[Na4] and [Ba3].} (11. Be3 $2 {A slow move allows Black to show their idea.} c4 $1 {Looking to trade off their doubled pawn and open the position for the bishops.} 12. d4 {, we should keep the center closed. After} Rb8 13. Rb1 {⩲ , White maintains the advantage, but now Black can continue putting pressure on our [b2]-pawn. We never really want to play [b3] since ...[cxb3] will be good for Black. This means we'll be stuck defending the [b2]-pawn with pieces as the game progresses, which isn't ideal for us.}) *

