{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 10. Be3 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge3d4] A prophylactic move that secures the center better while also making it more difficult for Black to play pawn breaks like ...[d5] and ...[e5].} (10. O-O $6 {was played in the game, but this allowed Black to fight back against White's center more effectively.} d5 11. e5 Ne4 {and compared to playing [Be3] on move one, White cannot trade knights on [e4] here without losing the [d4]-pawn.} 12. Nxe4 $4 dxe4 13. Ng5 Qxd4 {-+ , Black would be much better now since there is no bishop on [e3].}) 10... d5 {Black could try attacking our center but with the bishop on [e3], it is less effective.} (10... e5 11. d5 {± , we sidestep the [e5]-pawn and gain a bigger space advantage. Aside from the knight being attacked, Black's [g7]-bishop is heavily restricted now too.}) 11. e5 {Sidestepping the pawn and advancing into Black's half of the board.} Ne4 {This move doesn't work so well now that the bishop is already on [e3].} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gg5e4] The [d4]-pawn is safe and solid, while Black has trouble defending their [e4]-pawn in the long term.} *

