{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 15. Rc1 $1 {Preparing to ply [Nc3] without allowing the ...[b5] pawn break to chip away at our center. We line up with Black's queen and prevent the pawn break because of discovered attacks.} (15. Nc3 $6 {We have to be careful how we develop and work around Black's queenside pawn break. This move allows Black's idea.} b5 {, Black takes advantage of the c-pawn being pinned. After} 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Bd7 {∞ , White has a space advantage in the position, but it is not easy to use it. Black will fight for control of the c-file and it isn't easy to make progress as White.}) (15. Nd2 {∞ develops the knight in a way that doesn't walk into a pin on the c-file, but the knight is far away from the weak [d5]-square.}) (15. a4 $6 {We may try to prevent ...[b5] this way but actually by leaving our [b3]-pawn undefended, we are allowing Black's pawn break: (15...[b5] ∞.) We cannot win the pawn due to the [b3]-pawn being undefended.}) 15... Rfc8 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gb7b5,Gd6d5] Black adds another piece to target down the c-file. The idea is still to play ...[b5] or ...[d5] and take advantage of the pin towards the [c1]-rook.} 16. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Re4][%cal Gb7b5,Gc4b5,Gd6d5,Gc4d5] Now it is safe to play [Nc3] since the knight is supported. Black has a hard time fighting against our center since the ...[b5] and ...[d5] pawn breaks have been prevented.} (16. a4 $2 d5 $1 {Black is able to pull off the other pawn break against our center due to the pin on the c-file.} 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5 $4 {This doesn't win material but instead loses it.} Qxc1+ 19. Bxc1 Rxc1+ 20. Bf1 {, playing [Kf2] runs into ...[Bc5]+ problems.} Bh3 {-+ , Black threatens ...[Bc5]+ followed by capturing on [f1]. White will lose material and have a terrible position.}) *

