{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 12. h3 {By kicking the black bishop around, we will either gain the bishop pair or weaken Black's pawn structure.} Bh5 (12... Bxf3 $6 13. Qxf3 {± and we've gained a new advantage. We already had the space advantage, but now we also have the bishop pair.}) 13. g4 $1 {Despite slightly weakening our king, forcing Black's bishop back to [g6] is actually very good for us.} Bg6 14. Bxg6 $16 {[%cal Gf7g6,Gh7g6,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] It might be surprising that slightly weakening our king and trading off our good bishop is the best way to play in the position. The main problem for Black is that once they recapture on [g6], their pawn structure will be inflexible and make it difficult for them to make a pawn to chip away at our central pawns. If they recapture with the f-pawn as happened in the game then there is no more ...[f6] pawn break and our center will be very secure. If they recapture with the h-pawn, then any ...[f6] pawn break later will leave the [g6]-pawn weak and we can look to attack that pawn. Also, once Black has one of their pawns pulled to the [g6]-square, then this opens up [h4]-[h5] pawn breaks for us, which can be useful to help us attack their kingside once they castle.} *

