{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 21. h5 {Black has no threats or immediate counterplay on the queenside so we can press forward with our kingside play. We want to open the h-file for our rook.} g5 {Black tries to keep the h-file closed but gives themselves a potentially weak pawn.} 22. h6 $18 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g7] This is another strong pawn advance. We are still looking to open Black's kingside and also semi-isolate Black's [g5]-pawn. If Black trades pawns, then our rook becomes very dangerous. If they play ...[g6] instead, the [g5]-pawn becomes a weak pawn that we can attack with moves like [Qd2] and [Ng1]-[f3].} (22. Qd2 $2 {targets the [g5]-pawn but gives Black the chance to secure the pawn and lock the kingside structure:} h6 {⩲ . Now it's more difficult to attack on the kingside. We would have to work towards an [f4] pawn break, but that would come at the cost of weakening our king.}) *

