{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 16... Nh5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh5g3] We're ahead a pawn and have the chance to trade a pair of pieces by using a few forcing moves. First, we begin by attacking White's queen who is stuck defending their knight.} 17. Qg5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg5h5] Keeping their knight defended while also attacking ours.} (17. Qe1 $6 {would make life very easy for us.} Qxe1 18. Raxe1 Nf6 {-+ and we're simply ahead a pawn in the endgame without queens on the board. Converting the material advantage is easier without the queens.}) 17... f6 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rg5][%cal Gf6e5,Gf6g5] Forking the two pieces. We don't win material since our own knight is hanging but we do guarantee a trade of pieces.} 18. Qxh5 Qe3+ {It's most precise to throw this check in to push White's king into the corner first.} (18... Qxe5 {∓ , capturing with the queen immediately is also good but slightly less precise than inserting the check first.}) (18... fxe5 $6 {, capturing with the pawn gives us an isolated e-pawn while queens are still on the board. After} 19. Rfe1 Qf5 20. Qxf5 Rxf5 21. Rad1 {∓ , we still have the advantage, but White's rooks have been able to activate more than we would have liked.}) 19. Kh1 (19. Rf2 $2 {Blocking with the rook creates trouble for White:} fxe5 {-+ . The rook on [f2] is pinned and being targeted along the f-file now.}) 19... Qxe5 $19 {Now we capture the knight. We're still ahead one pawn and have been able to simplify the position, which increases our winning chances. Less pieces on the board mean less complexity and counterplay for White. Even if White avoids the queen trade with a move like [Qf3], then we can play ...[c6] with a solid advantage due to the extra pawn.} *

