{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 28. Ne3 $18 {[%cal Gc3d1,Gc1c2,Ge2d3,Gf3f4,Gd2c3,Gb2b4] It's important to keep as many pieces on the board as possible when you have the space advantage unless you have a really good reason to make a trade. Here Black would love to trade off their bad dark-squared bishop, which was stuck behind all their central pawns. On the other hand, we should want to keep our good dark-squared bishop alive. Moving the knight to [e3] interferes with the diagonal. If Black wants to trade off their bad bishop now, then it will mean that White gains the bishop pair advantage in return. If Black doesn't trade pieces on [e3] then White can slowly build the position with moves like [Ncd1], [Qc2], [Bd3], and [Bc3] and eventually play the [b4] or [f4] pawn break after preparation.} (28. Bxh6 {± was played in the game, but White should have tried to keep this pair of bishops on the board.}) (28. f4 {± , pushing the f-pawn blocks the diagonal and prevents the trade, but it is probably a bit hasty and weakens White's [e4]-pawn a bit.}) *

