[GameId "2133654363507013"]

{What is the best way to play to work towards converting our long-term advantage?} 10. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf3f4] Since the center is under White's control, it is now time for White to expand towards the kingside and begin to build an attack using a pawn storm. In opposite-side castling positions, this is usually an important idea anyway, but it is especially helped by the fact that we have an advantage in the center of the board first. We should push the g-pawn first because following up with [g5] soon will create a quick threat.} (10. f4 $2 {gains space but weakens the [e4]-pawn and [g4]-square.} b5 {, Black is ready to play ...[b4] next. After} 11. e5 Ng4 {∞ , Black gets more piece activity and will be able to make some piece exchanges soon.}) (10. h4 {⩲ , pushing the h-pawn is not as good since it will take a longer amount of time for the h-pawn to create a threat compared to pushing the g-pawn.}) 10... Nd7 {Black gets out of the way of the g-pawn and prevents White from advancing further for the moment.} (10... b5 {, Black could try to generate their own queenside play, but White is faster on the kingside:} 11. g5 Nd7 12. f4 b4 13. Nd5 {+- . Even without attacking the kingside, White's space advantage is making things very difficult for Black. None of their minor pieces have any good moves. White will play [h4]-[h5] and continue pushing on the kingside to work towards opening up Black's king.}) 11. f4 $18 {[%cal Gf4f5] Gaining more space, threatening [f5] to trap the bishop, and also preventing either of Black's knights from using the [e5]-square. White's space advantage is really starting to suffocate Black.} (11. h4 $5 {was played in the game, but Black was able to cycle a knight through the [e5]-square to get more activity and unblock their c-pawn. Following} b5 12. g5 Nce5 {± , White still has the advantage and went on to win, but playing [f4] earlier would have prevented the ...[Nce5] and ...[c6] ideas.}) *

